cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Distinguishing ICs from employment/servant relationship:
  (i) Distinction turns on principal/employer's right to control the manner and method by which a person performs their job;
  (ii) Employment relationship: employee is compensated on a time basis (e.g., per hour, per year, etc.); employer has a right to control the manner and method by which employee performs the job;
  (iii) IC relationship: IC hired to do a particular job; paid a given amount for the particular job; principal has limited rights to control the manner and method in which IC performs;
(2) Principal's liability for IC acts:
  (i) public policy dictates that principals should be liable for certain torts committed by independent contractors;
  (ii) Principals can be held liable for independent contractor torts where:
  (a) Inherently dangerous activities (acts performed by IC that are, by nature, inherently dangerous);
  (b) principal knowingly hires an incompetent independent contractor.

