cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Venue in original district is proper: court may order transfer based on interest of justice, convenience of parties and witnesses. Court's discretion based on
  (i) Public factors-what law applies, which community should be burdened with jury service, etc;
  (ii) Private factors-convenience (e.g., location of evidence, witnesses);
(2) Venue in original district is improper: court may transfer in the interest of justice or dismiss the case;
(3) Choice of law: transferee court applies choice of law rules of the original court, regardless of which party sought transfer. Exception: transferee court will apply its own laws if original venue was improper;
(4) Forum selection clauses: case must be transferred to the indicated fed. district unless the public factors present a compelling reason not to transfer.

