cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Rule 12 (b) defenses:
  (i) Lack of SMJ;
  (ii) Insufficiency of service of process*;
  (iii) Lack of PJ*;
  (iv) Failure to state a claim;
  (v) Improper venue*;
  (vi) Failure to join a necessary party;
  (vii) Insufficiency of process.*
(2) Rule 12 (b) defenses may be raised by motion or in the answer. Must be filed before an answer if a responsive pleading is allowed;
(3) Motion for more definitive statement (Rule 12 (e)): if complaint is so vague or ambiguous that D cannot reasonably prepare a response, D may move for a more definitive statement from P;
(4) Motion to strike (Rule 12 (f)): D may move to strike from the complaint (or court may strike on its own) any redundant, immaterial, impertinent, or scandalous material;
(5) Motion for judgment on the pleadings (Rule 12 (c)): P or D may move for judgment on the pleadings when the complaint plus the answer reveal that one party must win. E.g., D's answer admits all allegations in P's complaint; P must win.

