cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Necessary parties: absentees are necessary when either-
  (i) Without absentee, court cannot grant complete relief, consider whether multiple suits might follow if absentee is not made a party;
  (ii) Absentee has a legal interest that may be impaired or impeded;
  (iii) Absentee has an interest that creates a risk of multiple or inconsistent rulings and obligations.
(2) Requirements: absentee can be joined as a necessary party if­
  (i) There is PJ over the absentee;
  (ii) Joining the absentee will not destroy diversity.
(3) Indispensable parties: if a necessary party cannot be joined, ask whether the party is so indispensable that the case should be dismissed; court looks at these factors:
  (i) Is an alternative forum available?;
  (ii) What is the likelihood of prejudice to the parties or others if the case goes forward?;
  (iii) Can the court shape potential relief to avoid prejudice?;
  (iv) Would P have an adequate remedy if the case is dismissed?

