cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Intervention as a right: must be allowed if either
  (i) Absentee's interest will be harmed if not joined and no existing party will adequately represent that interest, or.
  (ii) Absentee has an unconditional statutory right.
(2) Permissive intervention: allowed in court's discretion if either-
  (i) Absentee has a claim or defense that shares a common question of law with the underlying action;
  (ii) Absentee has a conditional statutory right;
  (iii) Absentee is an officer or agency and an existing claim or defense relates to the officer/agency or a statute, regulation, etc.
(3) Jurisdiction: In diversity cases, interveners must establish independent SMJ. Supplemental jx will not cover diversity intervention;
(4) Intervention vs. compulsory joinder: compulsory joinder forces absentee into suit; narrow; must be very necessary for the court to force an absentee into a case. Intervention lets absentee join suit voluntarily; more lenient.

