cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Procedure:
  (i) P files motion for default judgment against D;
  (ii) Clerk enters default on docket if P shows that D failed to respond within 21 days of being served (60 days if service waived);
  (iii) Default does not automatically entitle P to recovery;
  (iv) clerk or judge must enter judgment of default;
(2) Default judgment by court clerk: may be entered if
  (i) D has not responded at all;
  (ii) Claim is for money damages;
  (iii) P gives an affidavit of sum owed;
  (iv) D is not a minor or incompetent;
(3) Default judgment by court: if elements above are not met, court may still enter default judgment and hold hearing on damages D may be entitled to hearing. If D has appeared at some point in response to P's complaint, D must get 7 days notice of a hearing on default motion;
(4) Recovery: limited to amount demanded in complaint;
(5) Setting aside default judgment: court may set aside default judgment for good cause shown within one year; usually satisfied if D can show excusable neglect, mistake, or fraud.

