cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Right to a jury trial:
  (i) 7th Amendment: provides the right to a jury trial in civil actions at law, but not at equity (i.e., not where equitable relief sought);
  (ii) Demand for jury trial: may be included in any pleading;
  (ii) Deadline: must be made within 14 days of service of the last pleading raising a triable issue; otherwise, waived;
  (iii) Number of jurors: minimum of 6 jurors, maximum of 12;
  (iv) Verdict: unless the parties stipulate otherwise, the verdict must be returned by at least 6 members and be unanimous;
  (v) Cases involving law and equity claims: jury will decide underlying facts on claim at law first; equity claims left for judge to decide.
(2) Voir dire:
  (i) Jury selection process: each party may strike jurors, either for cause or through peremptory challenges;
  (ii) For-cause strikes: used to strike potential juror for cause E.g., bias, prejudice, relation to party Each side has unlimited for-cause strikes;
  (iii) Peremptory strikes/challenges: each side has 3, which can be used for any race-neutral and gender-neutral purpose.
(3) Non-jury trial: parties can elect for trial on documentary evidence alone or for a non-jury (bench) trial. Judge must make fact findings and state separate conclusions of law.

