cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Interlocutory orders reviewable as of right:
  (i) Injunctions: orders concerning an injunction
  (ii) Receivers: orders concerning appointment of receivers
  (iii) Patent: orders where only an accounting is left in the case
  (iv) Property: orders affecting property (e.g., attachment)
(2) Interlocutory Appeals Act: appellate court may hear appeal of a non-final order if trial judge certifies that the order involves a controlling issue of law with substantial ground for difference of opinion;
(3) Class action: appellate court may review an order granting or denying class certification;
(4) Collateral order exception: appellate court may hear an interlocutory appeal on an issue if it is:
  (i) too distinct from the merits of the case (i.e., collateral);
  (ii) too important to be denied review;
  (iii) would essentially be unreviewable if parties waited for final judgment;
(5) Extraordinary writ: a party aggrieved by an unappealable order may seek a writ to compel or prohibit lower court action; must show irreparable harm will occur and normal route of appeal is inadequate.

