(1) Requirements:
  (i) Same parties: the second case was brought by the same party against the same party (e.g., same P against same D). An entity in privity with a party is considered "same party" (e.g., an employee and employer are the same party for claim preclusion purposes);
  (ii) Same claim: same claims in the first and subsequent suit. Claim refers to the transaction or series of transactions or occurrences giving rise to the action. Even if not previously raised, claim can be precluded if it is sufficiently related to prior claims;
  (iii) Final judgment on the merits in original claim: Judgment is final even if it is being appealed. Dismissal with prejudice operates as a judgment on the merits. Technical dismissals (SMJ, PJ, Venue) are not "on the merits" because they are not evaluating the substance of the plaintiff's claim.

