cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Defensive use of prior judgment:
  (i) D seeks to prevent P from re-litigating an issue P lost in a prior suit against a different party;
  (ii) Allowed if the party against whom issue preclusion is asserted had a full chance to litigate the issue previously;
  (iii) For Example: D in second case can preclude P from re-litigating an issue P lost to another D in a prior case; this is "non-mutual" because the party asserting IP was not a party in the prior litigation.
(2) Offensive use of prior judgment:
  (i) P seeks to prevent D from re-litigating an issue that D previously lost in a prior suit against a different party;
  (ii) highly disfavored and rarely allowed;
  (iii) Court will allow only if deemed fair after balancing factors;
  (iv) Factors:
(1) Whether party against whom prior judgment is asserted had full and fair opportunity to litigate;
(2) Whether party could foresee multiple suits being filed;
(3) Whether the party asserting IP controlled or could have joined the prior litigation;
(4) There are no inconsistent judgments on the record.

