cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Under the 10th Amendment, all powers not granted to the federal government, nor prohibited to the states, are reserved to the states. Limits Congress's ability to regulate and/or tax states alone; Congress cannot require states to enact laws or administer federal law; Exception: Civil rights; Congress may restrict state activities that violate civil liberties; Dual application: regulations applying to both public and private sector are usually valid (e.g., federal minimum wage laws are applicable to state/local government as well as private sector);
(4) Conditional grants:
  (i) Congress can induce (but not compel) state regulatory or legislative action through the use of conditional grants. E.g., federal highway funds conditioned on states maintaining a minimum drinking age of 21;
  (ii) Requirements:
  (a) Condition must be expressly stated;
  (b) Condition must relate to the purpose of the law at issue;
  (c) Condition cannot be unduly coercive.

