cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Limitations on delegation:
  (i) Congress must provide intelligible standards to define the scope of legislative authority it delegates;
  (ii) Congress may not delegate executive or judicial powers to itself or its officers (e.g., Congress cannot create commissions that enforce or prosecute violations of law);
  (iii) Note: b/c the delegation power is broad, be wary of answer choices regarding excessive delegation as a limitation on congressional authority;
(2) Legislative & line-item vetoes:
  (i) Unconstitutional;
  (ii) Legislative veto: Congress cannot veto a decision by an agency acting pursuant to delegated power; must be overturned by enacting a superseding law;
  (iii) Line-item veto: President cannot veto part of a bill; would be impermissible delegation of power to the President; President must sign or veto a bill in its entirety.

