cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Rational basis: a law will be upheld if it is rationally related to a legitimate govt. purpose.
  (i) Any conceivable legitimate purpose suffices, regardless of the actual purpose of the law;
  (ii) a law will almost always be upheld under rational basis review unless it is completely irrational or arbitrary;
  (iii) Burden of proof: challenger bears the burden of proof;
(2) Intermediate scrutiny: a law will be upheld if it is substantially related to an important govt. purpose.
  (i) Govt. goal must be important;
  (ii) courts look at the actual reason the law was enacted;
  (iii) Burden of proof: govt. bears the burden of proof;
(3) Strict scrutiny: a law will be upheld if it is necessary to achieve a compelling govt. interest.
  (i) Govt. must show there are no less restrictive or burdensome means of achieving its goal;
  (ii) courts look at the actual reason the law was enacted;
  (iii) Burden of proof: govt. bears the burden of proof.

