cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Economic rights:
  (i) Rational basis test;
  (ii) Const. provides only minimal protection for economic liberties (laws affecting or amounting to a taking of one's economic rights);
  (iii) Rational basis applies unless the infringement falls under the Contract Clause (see below) or Takings Clause;
  (iv) Govt. almost always wins under the rational basis test
(2) Contract Clause:
  (i) States cannot impair existing contractual duties;
  (ii) Applies only to state/local interference with existing contractual obligations, including govt. obligations;
  (iii) Levels of scrutiny are different for private vs. public contracts:
  (a) Private contracts require intermediate-type scrutiny, if a law substantially impairs a party's rights under an existing contract, it violates the Contract Clause unless the law;
  (i) serves an important, legitimate public interest;
  (ii) is reasonable and narrowly tailored in promoting that interest;
  (b) Govt. contracts require stricter scrutiny; local laws substantially impairing or interfering with existing govt. contracts must be reasonable and necessary to serve an important public purpose.

