cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Ex Post Facto Clause: prohibits ex post facto laws.
  (i) Test: a law is an ex post facto law if it either
  (a) criminally punishes conduct that was lawful when done;
  (b) increases punishment for a crime after it has been committed;
  (c) reduces the burden required to convict a person for a crime after it has been committed;
  (ii) Does not apply to civil liability, where retroactive legislation must meet only rational basis. Note: Ex Post Facto Clause is contained in the Contracts Clause;
(2) Bill of attainder: legislative acts that punish specific individuals or group members without a judicial trial. E.g., an order to imprison a person without judicial process Bills of attainder are prohibited under the Const.

