cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Classifications benefitting minorities (affirmative action);
(2) Numerical set-asides (quotas): to be valid, requires clear proof of persistent and readily identifiable discrimination, which cannot be based on general past wrongs. Quotas are unlikely to be upheld;
(3) Admissions:
  (i) b/c student body diversity may be a compelling interest, educational institutions may use race or national origin as a factor in admissions decisions, but not as a defining criterion. E.g., invalid to award "points" to applicants based on race;
  (ii) Universities must show that no workable race-neutral alternatives would assure the diversity sought;
(4) Public school integration: public school systems may not assign students to schools on the basis of race to achieve integration. Generally, racial balancing is not a compelling state interest.

