cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Right to travel:
  (i) Strict scrutiny;
  (ii) Usually arises when laws impede movement between states;
  (iii) Durational residency requirements are laws requiring some period of in-state residency to qualify for a state benefit;
  (iv) Invalid residency requirements include 1-year residency to receive welfare; 1-year residency to receive subsidized medical care; 1-year residency to vote in state elections;
  (v) Valid residency requirements include 30-day residency to vote in state elections; 1-year residency to get a divorce;
(2) Right to vote:
  (i) Strict scrutiny;
  (ii) Arises with laws that deny some citizens the right to vote;
  (iii) The "one person, one vote" requirement must be met for all state and local elections;
  (iv) For elected bodies, voting districts must be similar in population;
  (v) At-large elections the laws can be constitutional, when all voters vote for all office holders.

