cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Strict scrutiny applies: prior restraints are difficult to uphold. Often arises as court order/injunction preventing speech.
(2) Requirements: to be valid, a prior restraint requires:
  (i) Govt. interest: there must be at least some significant govt. interest justifying the restraint (i.e., a special societal harm). National security may be a sufficient harm/govt. interest, but the harm must be more than theoretical;
  (ii) Procedural safeguards: for those whose speech is restrained; safeguard must ensure restraint is narrow, reasonable, and definite; and provides for prompt, final judicial determination;
(3) Preliminary injunction: to prevent pretrial discussion in order to preserve a fair trial; only valid if it's the only way of preserving a fair trial. Note: P must comply with valid injunction until it is vacated or overturned; P cannot challenge a violated injunction;
(4) Permits/licensing: govt. may require licenses or permits for speech only if it has a reasonable justification for doing so. Requirements for permit/license must be similar to a "rubber stamp" process and must provide review for denied permits/licenses. P can challenge a denial on constitutional grounds, even if violated.

