cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Free Exercise Clause:
  (i) prohibits govt. from punishing someone solely on the basis of that person's religious beliefs or conduct;
  (ii) Govt. action must be necessary to achieve a compelling interest, but Court has never upheld religious punishment under this standard. Limitation: only applies if the purpose of a govt. act is to limit or interfere with religious practice or beliefs; acts of general applicability (i.e., not designed to regulate or interfere with religion) are valid.
(2) Establishment Clause: prohibits govt. acts that establish/sponsor religion or give preference to one religion over another. Lemon Test (government act concerning religion is only valid if):
  (i) There is a secular purpose behind the act;
  (ii) Act's primary effect neither advances nor inhibits religion;
  (iii) Act does not create excessive govt. entanglement with religion.

