cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Analysis (government interference with association is valid only if):
  (i) Government act is in pursuance of a compelling government interest;
  (ii) That interest cannot be achieved by less restrictive means. Note: This test is largely analogous to strict scrutiny;
(2) Restrictions on group discrimination: a government law or regulation may be invalid if it interferes with a group's expressive activities. Usually involves groups formed for expressive, non-intimate purposes (e.g., NAACP, KKK). E.g., KKK not required to accept non-white members because this exclusion is integral to its organizational message;
(3) Laws criminalizing membership: government must prove that defendant
  (i) Actively affiliated with a group involved with illegal activities;
  (ii) Had knowledge of the group's illegal activities;
  (iii) Acted with the specific intent of furthering those activities;
(4) Disclosure requirements: strict scrutiny if chilling effect. Laws requiring disclosure of group membership must meet strict scrutiny if disclosure would have the effect of chilling association (i.e., if it would inhibit the group's ability or willingness to associate).

