cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Under the Full Faith & Credit Clause ("FFCC") of the U.S. Const., a state court judgment must be recognized and enforced in other states I.e., a court in one state may not retry an issue that was properly decided in another state court proceeding; Note: If an issue is barred from re-litigation by virtue of the FFCC, it is unnecessary to do a further COL analysis; although FFCC applies only to state courts, use the same analysis when federal courts are the issuing and/or recognizing court. See 28 U.S.C. §§ 1738 & 1963; Analysis (courts must give full faith and credit to prior proceedings of U.S. states/territories unless there is a valid defense to recognition or enforcement):
  (i) Valid defenses (a court is not required to enforce another state's judgment if either):
  (a) Lack of jurisdiction ("jx"):
(1) Prior court did not have proper jx over parties and/or subject matter;
(2) Party challenging prior court judgment did not litigate the jx issue in the prior court;
  (b) Not on the merits: prior judgment was not on the merits (i.e., it did not involve the substance of P's claim); For Example: prior judgment is not on the merits if the action was dismissed for lack of subject matter jx;
  (c) No final judgment: prior court judgment was not final; Judgment is final when no further action by the court is necessary to resolve the litigation.

