cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Under the Second Restatement's Most Significant Relationship Approach, the court applies the law of the forum that has the most significant relationship to the issue at hand; Factors (in determining which forum has the most significant relationship, courts consider the following general factors):
  (i) Relevant policies of the forum and other interested jurisdictions;
  (ii) Relevant policies underlying the substantive field of law;
  (iii) Ease of applying the law to be applied;
  (iv) Whether application of a given law will aid certainty, uniformity, and predictability.
(3) Substantive areas of law (courts look at more specific factors depending on the type of case (e.g., torts, contracts, etc.)):
  (i) Torts: courts look at place of injury and conduct that caused the injury (most significant factor), as well as residence/domicile/place of incorporation of parties;
  (ii) Contracts: courts look at place of contracting, negotiation, performance, location of subject matter of contract, domicile/residence/place of incorporation of parties; generally, if place of negotiation and performance are the same, that forum's laws will be applied;
  (iii) Property: courts apply the law of the state most significantly related to the property transaction;
  (iv) Corporations: courts apply the law of the forum where corporation is incorporated.

