cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Express choice of law provisions in contracts are generally adhered to regardless of the conflict of law approach that would be applied by a court. Where no choice of law provision exists, courts will use one of the three conflict of law approaches; Exceptions (choice of law provisions in the contract will not be applied or honored where):
  (i) Contrary to public policy: applying the law of the contract-designated forum would conflict with a fundamental policy of a different forum that has a materially greater interest than the designated forum in determining the particular issue;
  (ii) No substantial relationship: contracting parties' chosen forum bears no substantial relationship to the parties or the transaction, such that there is no reasonable basis for the choice;
  (iii) Lack of consent: no true consent by all parties to the choice of the designated forum; can arise due to fraud, mistake, or contracts of adhesion;
(3) Default rules: Express choice of law provisions are always enforced with regard to default (as opposed to "mandatory") rules. Default rules are mere gap fillers that can be modified by agreement of the parties even in entirely local matters.

