cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Courts will give full faith and credit to divorce decrees issued in another state if:
  (i) The decree is valid in the other state;
  (ii) The other state had proper jx; satisfied if one of the spouses is domiciled in the state that granted the divorce;
(2) Ex parte divorce (divorce based on domicile of only one spouse):
  (i) Enforcing court may examine questions of domicile in determining whether full faith and credit should be given to the issued decree;
  (ii) Rebuttable presumption exists that spouse domicile is bona fide;
(3) Consent divorce:
  (i) Where both spouses are properly domiciled in the initial court granting divorce, full faith and credit will be given to the prior divorce decree if the prior court had proper jx;
  (ii) Jx will be found when at least one spouse is domiciled in the forum;
(4) Child custody:
  (i) Governed by reciprocal statutes adopted by all states;
  (ii) Generally, court has jx to make a custody determination if it is the child's home state; all other states must give that determination full faith and credit;
  (iii) Court making decree retains jx and no other state can modify the determination unless the original court had no significant connection with the child or parties in dispute.

