(1) In General: A contract ("K") is a promise or set of promises enforced by law; a legally enforceable agreement; Requirements to form a valid K (a K is formed when there exists):
  (i) Mutual assent: i.e., a meeting of the minds; Demonstrated by an offer and valid acceptance; Determined by parties' objective (not subjective) manifestations of assent;
  (ii) Consideration: A bargained-for exchange of legal value between the parties;
  (iii) No defenses to K formation: No defenses to formation exist that would invalidate the K;
  (iv) Void, voidable, & unenforceable Ks (if there is a valid defense to K formation or enforcement, a K may become):
  (a) Void: K never had any legal effect;
  (b) Voidable: one or both parties may elect to void the K;
  (c) Unenforceable: otherwise valid K that is unenforceable b/c a defense applies (e.g., incapacity, Statute of Frauds).

