cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Bilateral K:
  (i) Exchange of mutual promises;
  (ii) Each party is a promisor and promisee;
  (iii) For Example: A offers to sell his car to B for $5,000 and B promises to purchase A's car at that price;
(2) Unilateral K:
  (i) Offer requires performance as the manner of acceptance;
  (ii) Offeror-promisor agrees to pay upon completion of the act requested by the promisee; once act is completed, K is formed;
  (iii) For Example: A promises to pay B $100 if B paints A's fence; B is not obligated to paint A's fence, but if B does, K is formed and A must pay B $100;
(3) Quasi-contract:
  (i) Not a K, but rather a restitution remedy designed to prevent unjust enrichment;
  (ii) An implied-in-fact K arises when there is an unenforceable or non-existent agreement, but one side has realized a benefit;
  (iii) Look for: P has conferred a benefit to D; P reasonably expects to be paid; D knowingly accepted the benefit; and D will be unjustly enriched if P is not compensated.

