cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An objective manifestation of a present intent to contract; Demonstrated by a promise, undertaking, or commitment; definite and certain terms; and communication to an offeree; Objective manifestation of intent: offer must give offeree a reasonable expectation that offeror is willing to enter into a K; would a reasonable person believe the communication is an offer inviting acceptance?; Definite and certain terms: terms included must be sufficient to allow a court to enforce the K (e.g., quantity, time for performance, price, etc.); vague terms or terms of negotiation are insufficient; Communication to an identified offeree: offeree must know of the offer and have the power to accept it; for example, advertisements are generally not offers, unless highly specific as to quantity and clearly indicate who may accept; UCC offers:
  (i) Quantity must be certain or capable of being made certain;
  (ii) Requirement/output Ks: no unreasonably disproportionate increase in quantity allowed;
  (iii) Missing terms OK, particularly price, if parties clearly intended to make a K and there is a reasonably certain basis for giving a remedy.

