cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An offeror may revoke her offer, which effectively terminates the offer and the offeree's power of acceptance;
  (i) Unambiguous statement by the offeror to the offeree;
  (ii) Offeree becomes aware of offeror's unambiguous conduct or statement indicating an unwillingness or inability to contract;
(3) Limitations on revocation:
  (i) Revocation is only effective upon receipt by offeree;
  (ii) Offer cannot be revoked once it has been accepted;
  (iii) Unilateral Ks—start of performance makes the offer irrevocable for a reasonable time to complete performance;
  (iv) Start of performance must go beyond mere preparation;
(4) Irrevocable offers (offer will be irrevocable if):
  (i) Option K: promise to keep an offer open;
  (a) Common law: consideration required in exchange for option;
  (b) UCC: when UCC firm offer does not apply (see below), apply option K, where consideration is required;
