cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: rejection by offeree terminates the offer and the offeree's power of acceptance; Methods of rejection:
  (i) Express rejection: effective when received;
  (ii) Counteroffer: terminates original offer and becomes a new offer; bargaining or requests for information are not counteroffers;
  (iii) Conditional acceptance:
  (a) Terminates original offer and becomes a new offer (look for terms such as "if," "provided," "so long as," etc.);
  (b) For Example: offer to mow lawn; offeree says "I accept if you also trim the hedges"; this is a new offer; original offeree is now offeror;
  (c) Exception: a condition that would be included anyway (e.g., implied warranty) does not terminate original offer;
  (iv) Acceptance with additional terms:
  (a) Common law: acceptance must mirror the offer; acceptance with additional terms creates a rejection and counteroffer;
  (b) UCC: depends on whether both parties are merchants;
  (c) K involving non-merchant: terms of offer govern; K is formed, but additional terms are excluded and considered mere proposals to modify the K;
  (d) Both parties are merchants: additional terms become part of the K unless certain exceptions apply.

