cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Consideration is a bargained-for exchange of legal value between parties; there must be a benefit to promisor or detriment to promisee; this is a required element of every contract; "Bargained-for exchange": the promise must induce the detriment and the detriment must induce the promise;
  (i) Detriment: an obligation to do or refrain from doing something one would otherwise not be obligated to do or refrain from doing;
  (ii) Pre-existing duty: a promise to perform a pre-existing duty or obligation generally does not constitute consideration;
  (iii) Exception: promise to pay a debt after the statute of limitations has run is binding;
(3) Invalid consideration (the following is not consideration):
  (i) Promises of gifts or conditional gifts;
  (ii) Illusory promises: a promise where there is no obligation to perform (for example, A promises to do B's chores if he has time);
(4) Promissory estoppel (courts may enforce a promise if):
  (i) Promisor reasonably expects reliance by promisee;
  (ii) Promisee acts or refrains from acting in detrimental reliance;
  (iii) Injustice will occur without enforcement of the promise.

