cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) Infants and mentally incompetent persons lack capacity to contract;
  (ii) Intoxication: intoxicated persons may lack capacity to contract if the other party has reason to know of intoxication;
(2) Right to disaffirm: person who lacked capacity to contract (e.g., infant) may disaffirm the K, which renders it void; Infancy exceptions (Ks involving minors may be enforced or otherwise recognized where):
  (i) Implied affirmation (ratification): a K can be enforced against one who was an infant at the time of K formation if she has since gained capacity and retained benefits of the K;
  (a) Requirements:
(1) Agreement entered into before capacity;
(3) Benefits have been retained
  (ii) Infant liability for necessities: infants are legally obligated to pay for necessities (e.g., food, clothes, medical care); liability is based on quasi-K, so infant cannot be sued for breach (b/c there is not an enforceable K).

