cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A K may be unenforceable or void/voidable where there was a significant misunderstanding or mistake during K formation;
  (i) Neither party aware of ambiguity: no K formed unless both parties intended the same meaning;
  (ii) One party aware of ambiguity: K formed;
  (a) K enforced according to the intention of the unaware party; For Example: If A knows B misunderstands but A remains silent, K enforced according to B's understanding;
  (iii) Both parties aware of ambiguity: no K formed unless both parties intended the same meaning;
(3) Mutual mistake (both parties are mistaken about an underlying factual assumption at the time of K formation):
  (i) K is voidable by an adversely affected party if:
  (a) Both parties are mistaken concerning a basic assumption of fact;
  (b) Mistake materially affects the agreed-upon exchange;
  (c) Adversely affected party did not assume risk of the mistake;
(4) Unilateral mistake (one party makes a mistake concerning facts of an agreement; usually arises with computational errors):
  (i) Unilateral mistake will not prevent K formation;
  (ii) Exception: mistaken party may void K if mistake is material and non-mistaken party knew/should have known of mistake, or the mistake makes the contract unconscionable.

