cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Under the Parol Evidence Rule ("PER"), evidence that is extrinsic to a written K is inadmissible to supplement or contradict the written K; Applies if K is a complete integration: parties must intend the K to express their final agreement; existence of merger clause can be a factor in showing an agreement is integrated, but is not dispositive; PER bars evidence of:
  (i) Negotiations and agreements before K becomes integrated;
  (ii) Exceptions (extrinsic evidence may be allowed if either):
  (a) K was only partially integrated,
  (b) Additional terms would ordinarily be in a separate agreement;
(4) PER allows evidence of:
  (i) Mistake in the process of reducing an agreement to writing;
  (ii) Misrepresentation, fraud, duress, or illegality;
  (iii) Condition precedent to agreement becoming effective;
  (iv) Modifications (oral or written) made after the writing;
  (v) Meaning parties intended to give particular terms in the writing;
(5) UCC:
  (i) A written K's terms may be explained or supplemented by evidence of a course of dealing, performance, or trade;
  (ii) Can be used to show parties' customs take precedence over an industry's custom of trade;

