cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Under UCC Ks, risk of loss issues arise when goods are lost or destroyed; Shipment by carrier (e.g., FedEx), K type determines risk of loss ("ROL"):
  (i) Shipment Ks:
  (a) Seller only obligated to ship goods to buyer;
  (b) Risk of loss passes to buyer when seller delivers goods to carrier;
  (c) If K is otherwise silent on shipment terms, shipment K is presumed if K requires shipment by third-party carrier;
  (ii) Destination Ks:
  (a) Seller obligated to ensure goods reach buyer;
  (b) Risk of loss passes to buyer only when buyer takes delivery;
  (iii) Non-carrier delivery (goods not shipped by common carrier):
  (a) Merchant seller: ROL passes to buyer when he takes physical possession;
  (b) Non-merchant seller: ROL passes to buyer upon tender of delivery;
  (iv) Goods destroyed before ROL passes: K is avoided if no party at fault;
  (v) "FOB [location]":
  (i) Seller bears risk and expense of getting goods to the named location, at which point risk passes to buyer;
  (ii) For Example: A in Akron sells goods to B in Boise; K states "FOB Boise"; A is responsible for getting goods to Boise, then risk passes to B;
  (vi) Breach & ROL: if buyer rejects defective goods or revokes acceptance, ROL does not pass to buyer until defects are cured or she accepts.

