cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Under UCC Ks, seller's performance must be perfect with respect to the goods delivered and the manner of delivery; imperfect tender means seller sends defective/nonconforming goods; Buyer's options upon seller's imperfect tender (buyer can either):
  (i) Keep: retain goods delivered and sue for damages,
  (ii) Reject: reject some or all goods and sue for damages;
  (ii) Requirements (buyer who rejects goods must):
  (a) Notify seller of rejection in a reasonable time;
  (b) Hold the rejected goods using reasonable care;
  (c) Give seller reasonable time to arrange for removal of goods;
  (d) If seller gives no information regarding removal, buyer can return goods to seller, store goods for seller, or resell goods on behalf of seller (i.e., for seller's profit);
(3) Installment K (where delivery of goods occurs in separate lots):
  (i) Rejection (buyer can only reject a delivery/installment if):
  (a) Defect substantially impairs the installment;
  (b) Defect cannot be cured;
  (c) Rejection is limited to the defective installment, not the entire K;
  (d) Buyer can only cancel entire K due to a defective installment if the installment substantially impairs the entire K's value

