cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Conditions are agreed-upon limitations on performance in a K;
  (i) Performance is contingent on the occurrence of some event;
  (ii) For Example: A agrees to buy B's car if B gets new tires; B getting new tires is a condition of A's performance (buying the car);
  (iii) Indicated by: words such as "if," "provided that," "subject to," etc.;
  (iv) Condition vs. promise: failure of a promise leads to a breach; failure of a condition relieves a party's performance obligation;
(2) Types of conditions (conditions can be implied or express):
  (i) Condition precedent: condition must occur before performance due; non-occurrence excuses performance;
  (ii) Condition subsequent: condition that occurs after performance has begun and excuses duty to perform;
(3) Purpose controls interpretation:
  (i) Substantial performance of a condition may suffice if it fulfills the condition's purpose;
  (ii) Parties' intent controls: for example, if a condition is clearly designed to protect one party, it will be interpreted consistently with that intent;
  (iii) A party protected or benefitted by a condition may waive or estop the condition from being enforced;
(4) Excuse:
  (i) Conditions may be legally excused by breach, repudiation, etc.;
  (ii) A party whose performance is subject to a condition cannot prevent or hinder the condition's occurrence; will result in excuse of condition.

