cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Insecurity arises when a party to a contract has reasonable grounds to believe the other party will be unwilling or unable to perform; insecure party may demand adequate assurances and suspend performance in the meantime; applies under UCC and in many states to non-UCC contracts; Demand for adequate assurances:
  (i) Must be made in writing based on reasonable and justified grounds for insecurity;
  (ii) No response required if demand is unjustified or unreasonable (i.e., if party seeking adequate assurances is unreasonably insecure);
  (iii) Suspension of performance: a justifiably insecure party may suspend performance until adequate assurances are provided;
(3) Adequate assurances:
  (i) Commercially reasonable commitment (within 30 days) from a party that it will perform under the contract;
  (ii) If not provided, insecure party may treat contract as repudiated;
  (iii) Failure to respond to unreasonable demand is not a repudiation;
  (iv) If adequate assurances are provided, the formerly insecure party must perform; failure to do so will constitute a breach;
(4) Insecurity vs. anticipatory repudiation: Insecurity involves uncertainty regarding the other party's performance, whereas anticipatory repudiation involves a clear indication the other party will not perform.

