cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) Anticipatory repudiation (a.k.a. "repudiation") arises when one party to a K makes it clear that he will not perform under the K;
  (ii) Effect: excuses performance by the other party;
(2) Requirements (anticipatory repudiation arises if one party to a K):
  (i) Unambiguous act: makes an unambiguous statement or conduct;
  (ii) Prior to full performance: prior to the time performance is due;
  (iii) Indicating non-performance: which indicates he will not perform;
  (iv) For Example: A hires B to remodel A's kitchen. B is almost finished when A tells B she does not want the remodel and will not pay; B can treat K as breached, which excuses B's obligation to continue working;
  (v) Note: distinguish from insecurity, which involves mere uncertainty regarding other party's performance;
(3) Withdrawal (repudiation can be withdrawn unless other party has either):
  (i) Materially changed position in reliance on the repudiation;
  (ii) Cancelled the K in response to the repudiation;
  (iii) Indicated they consider the repudiation to be final;
(4) Non-repudiating party's options (she may either):
  (i) Treat the anticipatory repudiation as a total repudiation and sue;
  (ii) Suspend performance until performance date is due and wait to sue;
  (iii) Treat repudiation as an offer to rescind and treat K as discharged;
  (iv) Ignore repudiation and urge promisor to perform.

