cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: If an unforeseen event occurs after K formation but before performance is complete, performance may be excused as impossible or impracticable; Requirements:
  (i) An unforeseen event, which neither party assumed would occur, must make completing performance either:
  (a) Impossible: performance is objectively impossible;
  (b) Impracticable: performance is only possible with extreme and unreasonable difficulty or expense;
  (i) Substantial damage or destruction of K's subject matter;
  (ii) Damage or destruction must not have been either party's fault;
  (iii) Death: K obligations generally survive the death of a party, unless deceased party's K obligations are non-delegable (usually only unique personal services are non-delegable);
  (iv) Subsequent law or regulation (e.g., supervening illegality); if performance becomes illegal, excuse by impossibility.

