cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A party's duty to perform under a contract may be discharged if an unforeseen event occurs that undermines (frustrates) one or both party's principal purpose for entering into the contract; Requirements (a contract may be discharged if):
  (i) An unexpected event destroys one or both party's purpose for entering into the contract;
  (a) Whether performance is possible after the event is irrelevant;
  (b) Issue is whether performance after the unforeseen event nullifies one or both party's original purpose for the contract;
  (ii) The unforeseen event is not the fault of the frustrated party;
  (iii) The non-occurrence of the event was a basic assumption of the contract: Does not have to be a stated assumption in the contract;
  (iv) Frustration of purpose vs. impossibility:
  (a) Distinction is that impossibility concerns duties specified in the contract, whereas frustration of purpose concerns the reasons a party entered into the contract;
  (b) For Example: A landlord rents space to B restaurateur to open ice cream parlor; if the property is destroyed by an earthquake, A & B are excused from performing due to impossibility. However, if the city passes an ordinance banning the sale of sweetened food, the contract's purpose is frustrated because A knew B intended to open an ice cream parlor.

