cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A third party that benefits from a K entered into between other parties is a third-party beneficiary ("TPB");
  (i) Intended TPBs: parties to the K intend for TPB to benefit from the K; TPB has rights under the K;
  (ii) Incidental TPBs: stands to benefit from K although not intended by parties to the K; has no rights under the K;
(1) Determining TPB status: whether a TPB is an intended beneficiary under the K is a question of fact; courts look at the following factors:
  (i) Is TPB expressly designated in the K?;
  (ii) Does TPB directly benefit from some performance under the K?;
  (iii) Does TPB have rights under the K?;
  (iv) Does TPB stand in such a relationship to the promisee under the K that an intent to benefit the third party can be inferred?;
  (v) If answer to any of the above is "yes," more likely that TPB is intended;
(2) TPB characteristics:
  (i) Not parties to the K; TPBs are merely beneficiaries;
  (ii) Intended TPBs have a right to sue for breach of K even though they are not parties to the K;
  (iii) Creditor TPBs: benefit is conferred based on a debt owed by the promisee to the K;
  (iv) Donee TPBs: benefit is conferred gratuitously.

