cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) An assignment is a transfer of rights under a K to a third party after the K is formed;
  (ii) A party (assignor) can assign rights under a K to a third party (assignee), who is now in a K with remaining party (obligor);
  (iii) Consideration: not required, but assignment without consideration is considered gratuitous;
  (iv) Assignor can only transfer the rights they have in a K at the time of assignment;
(2) Common law limitations:
  (i) Common law bars any assignment that substantially changes the duties of the obligor;
  (ii) Assignment of payment is not a substantial change;
  (iii) Assignment of rights fails if the obligor's risk is substantially altered;
(3) K limitations on assignment (Ks may contain non-assignment clauses):
  (i) Non-assignment of K: bars delegation of assignor's duties only (i.e., does not prohibit assignment of rights);
  (ii) Non-assignment of rights: bars right to assign, but not the power to assign (i.e., upon assignment, obligor may sue assignor for breach);
  (iii) Assignment as void: assignment will be ineffective (i.e., assignor has neither power nor right to assign).

