cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) A delegation occurs when one party to a K (delegator) delegates the duties she owes to another party to the K (the obligee) to a third party (the delegatee);
  (ii) Obligee must generally accept performance from delegatee;
  (iii) Only duties may be delegated, whereas rights may be transferred to a third-party via assignment;
(2) Liability:
  (i) Delegator remains liable for delegatee's performance;
  (ii) Obligee may sue delegator for non-performance by delegatee;
  (iii) Obligee may only sue delegatee if the delegatee has assumed duties of the entire K;
(3) Exceptions (duties are non-delegable if):
  (i) Duties involve personal judgment and skill;
  (ii) Delegation materially changes the obligee's expectancy under the K;
  (iii) The K prohibits delegation;
  (iv) Prohibited by statute or public policy;
(4) Delegation vs. novation: Novation arises when both parties agree that a substitute person will take over duties under the K, whereas a delegation occurs when one party independently decides to delegate duties to a third party.

