cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Expectation damages:
  (i) Standard measure of money damages;
  (ii) Puts the parties in the economic position they would be in if the contract had been performed (i.e., if the breach never occurred);
  (iii) Note: when in doubt, look for the answer that most closely gives the damaged party what she would have received absent the breach;
(2) Reliance damages:
  (i) Alternative measure used when expectation damages are too speculative;
  (ii) Designed to compensate plaintiff based on the value of her performance and put plaintiff in the position they would have been in had the contract never been formed;
(3) Consequential damages:
  (i) Foreseeable losses indirectly resulting from a breach (e.g., lost profits); recoverable if:
  (a) Damages are a foreseeable result of the breach;
  (b) When contract was formed, defendant had reason to know plaintiff would suffer special, unpreventable, or unexpected damages in the event of a breach;
  (ii) UCC contracts: only buyers can recover;
(4) Incidental damages:
  (i) Commercially reasonable expenses incurred by the non-breaching party in UCC contracts (e.g., costs of inspecting, returning, storing, reselling goods);
(5) Duty to mitigate: plaintiff cannot recover reasonably avoidable damages, but can recover for costs of avoiding further damages.

