cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Restitution and liquidated damages are additional damage types that may be available;
  (i) Arise where a party has been unjustly enriched;
  (ii) Awarded based on value of the benefit wrongfully conferred;
  (iii) Party cannot recover both expectation damages and restitution damages;
(3) Liquidated damages:
  (i) Agreed-upon K provisions that stipulate specified damages upon the occurrence of a breach;
  (ii) Requirements: liquidated damages provisions are valid only if:
  (a) Damages are difficult to project at time of K formation;
  (b) The provision is a reasonable estimate of actual damages
(4) Duty to mitigate:
  (i) P cannot recover reasonably avoidable damages, for example, P must refrain from incurring additional losses after receiving notice of breach;
  (ii) P may recover for the cost of mitigation (for example, cost to avoid incurring further damages);
  (iii) Employment: P's damages can be reduced if D can show a comparable job in the same locale was available to P;
  (iv) D bears the burden of showing P's failure to mitigate.

