cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Centralized management: management rights are centralized in a board of directors ("BoD") who delegate day-to-day management to corporate officers; unlike partnerships, management is generally not spread among owners (i.e., shareholders);
(2) Limited liability: only the corp itself can be liable for its obligations; shareholders, board members, and officers are generally not liable for corp's obligations;
(3) Transferability of ownership: shareholders can freely transfer their ownership interests (i.e., shares) unless prohibited by articles or bylaws;
(4) Continuity: corps can exist in perpetuity; changes in ownership do not affect the corp's existence;
(5) Personhood: corps are considered "people" for most intents and purposes and are entitled to certain constitutional protections; E.g., corps are entitled to due process and equal protection.

