cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Ultra vires acts: where a corp acts outside of its stated purpose (as stated in articles of incorporation) it takes ultra vires acts; Consequences of ultra vires acts (three possibilities):
  (i) Shareholder suit: shareholders may sue corp to enjoin the ultra vires act;
  (ii) Corp suit: corp may sue an officer or director responsible for the ultra vires act for resulting damages;
  (iii) State action: state may bring action to dissolve the corp;
(3) De facto corp: where a corp's formation fails to adhere to proper formalities but it carries itself on as a corp; it may still be treated as a properly formed corp; De facto corp. Requirements:
  (i) A corporate law exists under which the entity could have become legally incorporated;
  (ii) A good faith effort to comply with the state's incorporation laws;
  (iii) The business acted like a corp (e.g., conducting business in its corp name);
(5) Corp by estoppel: persons who treat an entity as a corp are estopped from denying the entity is a corp, particularly in order to avoid liability.

