cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Debt securities (bonds): corp borrows funds from an outside creditor and promises to repay creditor. Holders of debt securities have no ownership interest;
(2) Equity securities (stocks, which is the instrument that represents investment in the corp; holders (i.e., shareholders) become part owners of the corp):
  (i) Authorized shares: max number of shares the corp may issue, as prescribed in the articles of incorporation;
  (ii) Issued/outstanding shares: shares that have been sold to investors;
  (iii) Reacquired shares: (i.e., those that the corp buys back) revert from being issued/outstanding to authorized;
(3) Classes of shares: corps may choose to issue different classes of stock shares; each class of shares can have different series within a class;
(4) Articles must authorize each class and set forth:
  (i) Number of shares of each class;
  (ii) Name or distinguishing designation for each class;
  (iii) Describe the rights, preferences, and/or limitations afforded to each class of shares.

