cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Shares authorized by a corporation can have different rights, preferences, and limitations depending on the class of shares. Articles can define almost any kind of differentiation between share classes; differences between share classes often involve:
  (i) Rights to distributions and/or dividends;
  (ii) Nature of voting rights;
  (iii) Preference with regard to distributions
(2) Distribution rights: corporation can distribute assets in the form of dividends, redemption of shares, or liquidating distributions upon dissolution. At least one class of shares must be entitled to receive the corporation's net assets upon dissolution
  (i) Board discretion: decision as to whether or not to declare a distribution is within the Board of Directors' sole discretion, even where the articles authorize distributions;
  (ii) Shareholders have no general right to demand a distribution;
(3) Consideration for shares: shares can be issued by the corporation in exchange for any tangible or intangible property or benefit to the corporation. For example, in some states, corporation can issue shares in exchange for anything of value, whether payment or services.

