cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Requirements for approval (mergers are considered fundamental corp changes and, as such, generally require each corp to get approval of):
  (i) Board: need a board vote by whatever vote authorizes board action (e.g., majority, supermajority);
  (ii) Shareholders: majority approval required;
  (iii) Exception: no significant change to surviving corp; surviving corp's shareholders need not approve of a merger where the surviving corp has no significant changes (e.g., articles do not differ post-merger, shareholders' shares and rights do not change, etc.);
(2) Effect: surviving corp owns all property and assumes all obligations of prior separate entities;
(3) Short-form merger: where a parent corp. owns at least 90% stock of a subsidiary, the subsidiary can be merged into the parent corp without approval of either corp's shareholders;
(4) Dissenters' rights:
  (i) dissenting shareholders can challenge the merger or demand payment for their shares at a fair market value;
  (ii) Mutual notice required: before a vote is taken on the merger, corp. must give shareholders notice and shareholders;
  (iii) if approved, corp. must pay dissenters fair market value for their shares.

