cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Dissolution (termination of the corp's existence):
  (i) Effect: corp continues to exist while it winds up and liquidates its affairs, but no other business may be carried out;
  (ii) Voluntary dissolution: considered a fundamental change and requires both board and shareholder approval;
  (iii) Administrative dissolution: action brought by state to dissolve corp; usually occurs due to failure to adhere to statutory requirements or formalities, but can be remedied by corporation;
  (iv) Judicial dissolution: action by attorney general or shareholders;
  (a) Attorney general can act to dissolve a corp on the ground that it abused its authority, committed fraud, etc.;
  (b) Shareholders can seek judicial dissolution where deadlock among BoD or shareholders threatens irreparable injury to corp, Corp has abandoned its business and failed to dissolve, or Corp's assets are wasted/misused for non-corp purpose;
(2) Disposition of property (where corp sells, leases, or otherwise disposes of all or substantially all property outside the regular course of business):
  (i) Deemed a fundamental change requiring shareholder/board approval;
  (ii) "Substantially all" = sale or disposition leaves corp without significant continuing business activities;
  (iii) "Outside regular course of business" = disposition is not considered a normal business activity for the corp.

