cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Specific intent:
  (i) D must have a specific intent or objective to commit the given crime;
  (ii) Specific intent must always be proven; never inferred;
  (iii) Mistake of fact and voluntary intoxication are defenses.
(2) General intent:
  (i) D must be aware of his actions and any attendant circumstances;
  (ii) May be inferred from the act itself;
  (iii) Note: most crimes are general intent crimes;
(3) Malice:
  (i) D acts with reckless disregard or undertakes an obvious risk, from which a harmful result is expected;
  (ii) Applies to arson and common law murder.
(4) Strict liability:
  (i) No intent or awareness required for strict liability crimes (i.e., no mens rea requirement);
  (ii) Arises with statutory rape, regulatory, or morality crimes;
(5) Vicarious liability:
  (i) Person without fault is held liable for another's criminal conduct;
  (ii) Often arises with employment or business associations.

