cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Concurrence requirement:
  (i) D's criminal act and the requisite intent (i.e., mens rea) for the crime must occur simultaneously;
  (ii) For Example: D plans on murdering victim at her home — D is not guilty of murder if he accidentally runs over victim with his car before reaching her house;
(2) Causation requirement:
  (i) D's conduct must be both the cause-in-fact and the proximate cause of the crime committed;
  (ii) Cause-in-fact:
  (a) but for D's conduct, the result would not have occurred;
  (b) Homicide and manslaughter: any act by D that hastens victim's death is a cause-in-fact, even if death is already inevitable;
  (iii) Proximate cause:
  (a) the actual result is the natural and probable consequence of D's conduct, even if it did not occur exactly as expected;
  (b) Superseding factors: break the chain of causation;
  (c) Intervening acts: must be entirely unforeseeable to shield D from liability (e.g., victim's refusal of medical treatment, third-party medical negligence — both are foreseeable and D is liable).

