cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: under the merger doctrine, two or more offenses merge, prohibiting D from being prosecuted separately for each crime;
  (i) Merger concerns the relationship between either:
  (a) an inchoate offense and its completed substantive offense,
  (b) an offense and its lesser included offense;
(2) Inchoate offenses:
  (i) Only applies to solicitation and attempt;
  (ii) Merger prevents D from being convicted of both solicitation/attempt and the target offense;
  (iii) For Example: D completes a burglary after attempting it; D cannot be convicted of both attempt and burglary;
  (iv) Does not apply to conspiracy (i.e., D can be convicted of conspiracy to commit a given crime and the crime itself).
(3) Lesser included offenses:
  (i) D cannot be convicted of a target crime and a lesser included offense;
  (ii) Lesser included offense: consists of same but not all elements as the greater crime;
  (iii) For Example: D robs V, but during the robbery D's accomplice kills V; D can be convicted of felony murder but not the lesser included robbery offense;

