cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Requirements (to be liable as an accomplice, one must):
  (i) Aid, counsel, or encourage principal before or during the crime;
  (ii) With the intent
  (a) to assist the principal;
  (b) that the principal commit the crime;
(2) Scope of liability: accomplice is liable for the crimes he committed or counseled and any other probable or foreseeable crimes committed;
  (i) Withdrawal: accomplice can avoid liability by withdrawing from a crime before the principal commits it; accomplice must:
  (a) Repudiate prior aid or encouragement;
  (b) Do all that is possible to counteract the prior aid;
  (c) Do so before the chain of events is in motion and unstoppable;
  (ii) Member of a protected class: those protected by a criminal statute are not liable as accomplices (for example, minor-victims in statutory rape cases are not liable as accomplices to statutory rape);
  (iii) Parties not provided for in the statute (for example, a purchaser of drugs cannot be an accomplice to the seller);
(4) Accessory after the fact:
  (i) different than accomplice liability;
  (ii) Involves helping a known felon escape arrest, trial, or conviction;
  (iii) Gives rise to a separate, lesser charge of obstruction of justice.

