cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Inciting, urging, or otherwise asking another to commit a crime with the intent that they commit the crime; no affirmative response from the solicited party is required; Merges with the target offense:
  (i) solicitation is complete when D asks solicitee to commit the felony;
  (ii) if solicitee agrees, it gives rise to conspiracy and the solicitation merges with the conspiracy (i.e., the only crime remaining is conspiracy);
  (iii) does not matter if the solicited party is convicted or if the solicited crime was impossible to commit;
(3) Defenses (there are very few defenses that apply to solicitation):
  (i) Refusal by the solicitee is not a defense;
  (ii) Impossibility and withdrawal are not defenses;
  (iii) MPC allows renunciation as a defense, but common law does not (most jurisdictions follow the common law approach).

