cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: An act, done with the specific intent to commit a crime, that constitutes an overt or substantial step towards committing the crime but falls short of completing the crime, or an incomplete act that would be a crime if completed); Overt act:
  (i) D must commit an act beyond mere preparation;
  (ii) D must take a substantial step towards committing the target crime;
  (iii) Under common law standard, attempt requires an act that is dangerously close to success;
(3) Intent: D must specifically intend to commit a particular crime; Defenses:
  (i) Legal impossibility is a defense to attempt;
  (ii) Factual impossibility is not a defense;
  (iii) Abandonment is not a defense; under majority rule, liability for attempt arises once D commits an overt act concurrently with the specific intent to commit a crime (i.e., D is liable for attempt before he can abandon the crime).

