cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Non-deadly force (may be used if D):
  (i) No fault: D is not at fault (i.e., not the initial aggressor);
  (ii) Reasonable belief of unlawful force: D reasonably believes it necessary to protect himself from imminent unlawful force;
  (iii) No duty to retreat;
  (iv) Allowable force: the amount of force permitted depends on the nature of the provoking offense; generally, it must be proportionate;
(2) Deadly force (may be used if D):
  (i) No fault: D is not at fault (i.e., not the initial aggressor);
  (ii) Confronted with unlawful force: attacker must use unlawful force;
  (iii) Reasonable belief of death or great bodily harm: D reasonably believes he is confronted with unlawful force that threatens imminent death or great bodily harm;
  (iv) No duty to retreat under majority rule.
(3) Self-defense by an initial aggressor (available if either):
  (i) Initial aggressor effectively withdraws before the need for self-defense arises and communicates his desire to do so;
  (ii) Victim of the initial aggression suddenly escalates a minor dispute into a deadly altercation;
(4) Defense of others:
  (i) same rules apply as for self-defense;
  (ii) D can defend another if D reasonably believes the person he is protecting could have legally defended himself.

