(1) Defense of dwelling:
  (i) Non-deadly force: allowed to prevent or terminate an unlawful entry or attack on one's dwelling;
  (ii) Deadly force: may be used if one reasonably believes
  (a) force is necessary to prevent attack on oneself or others by a person who made or attempted violent entry,
  (b) force is necessary to prevent entry by a person who intends to commit a felony in the dwelling;
(2) Defense of property (non-dwelling):
  (i) Deadly force not allowed;
  (ii) Non-deadly force may be used if reasonably necessary to defend against unlawful interference with possessions or trespass on property;
  (iii) Need to use force must reasonably appear imminent; force not permitted if request to desist is sufficient;
(3) Recovery of property:
  (i) Force is not allowed to regain property wrongfully taken, unless one is in immediate pursuit of the taker;
  (ii) For Example: D steals A's purse; A can only use reasonable force to recover purse if she is immediately pursuing D.

