cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Necessity: valid defense if D believed his conduct was reasonably necessary to avoid an imminent and greater injury to society;
  (ii) Objective standard: D's commission of the crime must be reasonably necessary; good faith alone is insufficient;
  (iii) Exceptions: necessity is not available if either
  (a) Crime committed results in the death of another,
  (b) D caused the events giving rise to the necessity;
(2) Duress: a valid defense to a crime D committed under reasonable belief that the crime was necessary to prevent death or serious bodily harm to D or a member of D's family;
  (i) For Example: someone points a gun at D and threatens to kill him if he does not rob a bank;
  (ii) Exception: duress is not a defense to intentional homicide crimes;
(3) Consent: consent of victim is generally not a defense, but may be available if it negates an element of the offense;
  (i) Never available for certain offenses (e.g., statutory rape);
  (ii) Requirements: must be established that
  (a) consent was voluntarily and freely given;
  (b) party was legally capable of consenting;
  (c) no fraud was involved in obtaining consent.

