cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Mistake of law:
  (i) almost never a defense;
  (ii) Lacking awareness or knowledge that an act constitutes a crime, even if reasonable, is not a defense to that crime;
  (iii) Exceptions: very rare, but can arise where either
  (a) Reasonable reliance on an invalid statute or official interpretation;
  (b) Mistake or ignorance negates an element of a crime requiring knowledge of the law;
(2) Mistake of fact:
  (i) available as a defense only if it negates a requisite intent element (i.e., mens rea) for the crime. Note: mistake includes ignorance
(3) Requisite mens rea element/Availability of mistake of fact defense:
  (i) Specific intent - Any mistake of fact is a defense;
  (ii) Malice and general intent - Only a reasonable mistake of fact is a defense;
  (iii) Strict liability (i.e., no intent) - Mistake of fact is never a defense.

