(1) Assault (two theories of assault at common law):
  (i) Assault as a threat (general intent crime):
  (a) Intentional creation of victim's reasonable apprehension of imminent bodily harm;
  (b) Words alone are usually insufficient;
  (ii) Assault as an attempted battery (specific intent crime):
  (a) Specific intent crime b/c it involves attempt;
  (b) Note: both of the above constitute assault for MBE purposes unless instructed otherwise;
(2) Battery (general intent crime):
  (i) an unlawful application of force to the person of another resulting in bodily injury or offensive touching (this is a completed assault);
  (ii) Note: under modern statutes, both assault and battery have "aggravated" counterparts, which usually arise when the assault or battery is carried out with the use of a weapon.

