(2) Felonies allowing for felony murder:
  (i) Inherently dangerous felonies;
  (ii) Statutorily enumerated felonies; a criminal statute will state that a killing occurring during its commission constitutes felony murder;
(3) Limitations on liability for felony murder:
  (i) D must be guilty of the underlying felony;
  (ii) Valid defenses to the underlying felony are also defenses to felony murder;
  (iii) The underlying felony itself must be independent of a killing;
  (iv) For Example: involuntary manslaughter cannot be felony murder;
  (v) Victim's death must be a foreseeable result (i.e., proximate cause) of the felony;
  (vi) Victim's death must be caused before D reaches a place of temporary safety;
  (vii) D is not liable for the death of a co-felon killed by police or the original victim in majority of states.

