  (ii) Subjective Standard: D was in fact provoked (i.e., D actually lost control);
  (iii) There was insufficient time for an ordinary person to cool off between the provocation and the killing;
  (iv) D did not cool off between the provocation and the killing;
  (v) Note: adequate provocation is not a defense to murder; however, it can be a mitigating factor that reduces a murder charge to voluntary manslaughter;
(3) Imperfect self-defense:
  (i) if D murders while acting in self-defense, his criminal liability can be reduced to voluntary manslaughter if either
  (a) D initiated the altercation that required self-defense,
  (b) D unreasonably believed deadly force was necessary;
  (ii) Note: not recognized in all jurisdictions.

