(1) General Rule:
  (i) The taking and carrying away;
  (ii) of another's tangible personal property;
  (iii) without consent (i.e., trespassory);
  (iv) with the intent to permanently dispossess the person of the property.
(2) Required elements:
  (i) Taking: obtaining control or possession; If D already has possession at the time of the taking, it is not larceny (but may give rise to embezzlement);
  (ii) Carrying away: the slightest movement will suffice;
  (iii) Without consent: against victim's free will (i.e., by trespass); the use of fraud or duress negates consent. Note: this element distinguishes larceny from larceny by trick;
  (iv) Intent to permanently dispossess:
  (a) must exist during taking;
  (b) Specific intent crime: not larceny if D takes property as security for a debt owed or believing it belongs to D;
  (c) Permanently: for an unreasonable period of time;
  (d) Continuing trespass: when one borrows property with the intent to return it, but later keeps it; larceny arises at the moment D decides not to return the property.
(3) Finding a lost item: larceny can arise if the true owner is known or ascertainable and D decides to keep the property (must be lost or misplaced; larceny cannot arise for abandoned property).

