cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Robbery:
  (i) wrongful taking;
  (ii) another's personal property;
  (iii) from his person or presence;
  (iv) by force or threat of injury;
  (v) with the intent to permanently deprive
(2) Robbery Requirements:
  (i) Robbery is assault or battery plus larceny;
  (ii) Victim's person or presence: interpreted broadly;
  (iii) Force or threat of injury: a small force or threat will suffice; threat of injury must be to victim, a member of her family, or a person in her presence; and victim must give up the property because she feels threatened or harmed; threats of future harm are insufficient;
  (iv) Larceny vs. robbery: robbery requires force or threats to obtain victim's property, whereas larceny does not; For example: a pickpocket commits larceny if victim did not notice his act, but commits robbery if victim notices;
(3) Extortion:
  (i) Obtaining property through threats of future harm or exposing information;
  (ii) Extortion vs. robbery: extortion does not require a taking from the victim's person or presence;
  (iii) Extortion involves threats of future, rather than immediate, harm.

