cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule:
  (i) Trespassory breaking;
  (ii) Entering into the dwelling house;
  (iii) of another;
  (iv) at nighttime;
  (v) the intent to commit a felony therein;
(2) Required elements:
  (i) Breaking: can be actual or constructive; must be trespassory;
  (a) Actual: opening or enlarging (e.g., opening an unlocked door);
  (b) Constructive: entry by threat, force, fraud, or duress; fraud negates any consent victim may have given;
  (c) Trespass required: entering with consent or through a wide open door is not a breaking; breaking not required under many modern statutes;
  (ii) Entering: placing any portion of the body or the instrument used for the breaking inside the dwelling;
  (a) Dwelling: structure used for sleeping purposes;
  (b) Modern statutes expand to include non-dwelling structures;
  (iii) Of another: ownership is irrelevant; occupancy will suffice;
  (iv) At nighttime: common law requirement; not a required element under modern statutes;
  (v) With the intent to commit a felony therein:
  (a) Modern statutes include misdemeanor thefts;
  (b) Felony need not be completed;
  (c) D must merely intend to commit a crime at the time of the breaking and entering;
  (d) Intent acquired after entering is insufficient;

