cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Probable cause is always required for any valid arrest:
  (i) Probable cause means trustworthy facts or knowledge sufficient for a reasonable person to believe that the suspect has committed or is planning to commit a crime;
(2) Warrants are rarely required for arrests:
  (i) Police generally do not need a warrant before arresting a person in a public place;
  (ii) Exception: non-emergency home arrests require a warrant and reasonable belief suspect is at home; meaning, police must have an arrest warrant to arrest an individual in their home;
  (iii) Police may only enter the home if they have reason to believe the suspect is in the home;
(3) Search warrant is required for police to execute an arrest of a suspect in a third-party's home:
  (i) A warrant is not required for an emergency arrest occurring in the arrestee's home.

