cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Govt. searches and seizures of evidence must be reasonable under the 4th Amend, which requires a valid search warrant, unless one of six exceptions applies.
(2) Determining the reasonableness of a search or seizure (Is there govt. conduct constituting a search or seizure?):
  (i) 4th Amend. only applies to govt. conduct (direct or authorized);
  (ii) Does not protect against private conduct;
  (iii) Authorized conduct: private persons acting at the direction of govt. agents constitutes govt. conduct;
(3) Does D have standing?:
  (i) D must have a reasonable expectation of privacy in the thing or place to be searched;
(4) Is there a valid search warrant?
(5) If there is no valid search warrant, was there a valid exception to the search warrant requirement? (Exceptions to the search warrant requirement):
  (i) Search incident to arrest;
  (ii) Plain view search;
  (iii) Automobile search;
  (iv) Valid consent to search;
  (v) Exigent circumstances;
  (vi) Stop & frisk.

