cards.backMarkdown:
(2) Requirements for a valid warrant:
  (i) Based on probable cause:
  (a) Usually a police affidavit demonstrating probable cause that the search or seizure will produce evidence;
  (b) Affidavits: must contain facts showing probable cause; may include information from anonymous sources;
  (c) If (1) there was a false statement; (2) affiant intentionally or recklessly included a false statement; and (3) false statement was material to finding probable cause, then warrant is invalid;
  (ii) Precise on its face:
  (a) warrant must describe, with reasonable precision, the place to be searched and/or items to be seized;
  (iii) Issued by a neutral and detached magistrate:
  (a) Good faith exception: exclusionary rule does not apply if police act in good faith on an invalid search warrant;
  (b) Exceptions to good-faith reliance: police cannot rely on a defective warrant obtained in good faith if:
(1) Affidavit completely lacks probable cause (i.e., no reasonable police officer would have relied on it);
(2) Warrant is defective on its face;
(3) Police or govt. official lied or misled magistrate;
(4) Magistrate has "wholly abandoned her judicial role."

