cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Police may search from any place where they are legitimately present when viewing (i.e., when conducting the search).
(2) Seizure based on plain view (police may seize evidence in plain view without a warrant if):
  (i) Police are legitimately on the premises from which they viewed the evidence to be seized;
  (ii) Criminal activity or contraband is immediately apparent;
  (iii) Police have probable cause to believe that plainly viewed evidence is contraband or relates to a crime;
(3) Scope of plain view searches:
  (i) Includes anything viewable from land or public property, even if only viewable through binoculars;
  (ii) Plain smell: included within plain view;
  (iii) If a smell gives rise to probable cause from a place of legitimate police presence, they can search that item;
(4) Limitations:
  (i) police cannot use technology not generally available to the public to view evidence that may constitute a plain view search (e.g., infrared scanners that can view through walls);
  (ii) Note: use of drones for plain view searches is unsettled law and thus unlikely to appear on the MBE.

