cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Police may detain a person for an investigative purpose if they have reasonable suspicion of criminal activity; Allowable scope of stop & frisk:
  (i) Length: detention must be no longer than necessary to verify the suspicion;
  (ii) Frisk: if police have reasonable suspicion the person is armed or dangerous, they may frisk for weapons;
  (iii) Plain feel: if police have reasonable belief during the frisk that what they feel is a weapon or contraband, they may seize the suspected item;
  (a) officers cannot manipulate the item to develop reasonable belief;
  (b) it must be plain touch only;
  (c) evidence validly seized is admissible;
(3) Stop vs. arrest:
  (i) A stop is a brief detention, less than an arrest;
  (ii) But police may develop probable cause to arrest based on anything occurring or discovered during the stop and/or frisk;

