cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: If exigent circumstances exist, police can search or seize evidence without a warrant; hot pursuit, evanescent evidence, and emergencies are forms of exigent circumstances justifying a warrantless search or seizure;
(2) Hot pursuit:
  (i) While actively pursuing a fleeing felon, police can search for anything relating to the pursuit or can search for their own protection;
  (ii) Permissible scope is as broad as reasonably necessary to prevent suspect from escaping or resisting;
  (iii) Police can enter into a private dwelling after attempting arrest in a public place if they have probable cause;
(3) Evanescent evidence:
  (i) Police can search or seize evidence that could disappear if police were required to secure a warrant;
  (ii) For Example: drugs that may be discarded, DNA evidence that may not last;
  (iii) Reasonableness judged by totality of the circumstances;
(4) Emergency:
  (i) Warrantless searches are justified for emergencies that threaten health or safety if not immediately acted upon;
  (ii) For Example: police see someone injured or threatened with injury, bomb threats, need to find source of a food or drug contamination;
  (iii) Whether an emergency exists is viewed objectively;

