cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Electronic surveillance (e.g., wiretapping, eavesdropping) that violates a reasonable expectation of privacy constitutes a search under the 4th Amend. and requires a warrant;
(2) Warrant requirements for electronic surveillance:
  (i) Probable cause that a specific crime is being or has been committed;
  (ii) Warrant must name suspects subject to surveillance;
  (iii) Warrant must describe with particularity the subject of conversations that can be surveilled;
  (iv) Surveillance must be limited to short periods of time;
  (v) Surveillance must terminate when desired information is obtained and must be turned over to the court;
(3) All speakers assume the risk that the person to whom they are speaking is wired and/or recording the conversation:
  (i) Therefore, police do not need a warrant if they get someone to wear a wire and talk to the suspect;
  (ii) A speaker who makes no attempt to keep a conversation private has no reasonable expectation or privacy.

