cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Prohibits the introduction of evidence obtained in violation of D's constitutional rights in a criminal trial;
  (i) Evidence derived or obtained from illegal govt. conduct is excludable against D;
  (ii) Arises when illegal police action leads to evidence;
(3) Exceptions (illegally obtained evidence is admissible if government can "break the chain" between the illegal govt. conduct and the seized evidence; common ways to break the chain):
  (i) Independent source: govt. had an independent source for obtaining the evidence, i.e., independent from the original illegality;
  (ii) Inevitable discovery: govt. would have discovered illegally derived evidence even without illegal conduct;
  (iii) Attenuation: where evidence challenged is too remote and attenuated from unlawful search or seizure; includes intervening acts of free will by D (e.g., after initial illegality, D consciously leads police to the evidence);
(4) Remedy for exclusionary rule violation:
  (i) Harmless error review;
  (ii) For admission of illegally-seized evidence to be upheld on appeal, govt. must show that it was harmless beyond a reasonable doubt.

