cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: The exclusionary rule applies only to searches in violation of a fed. statute or the U.S. Constitution
(2) Exclusionary rule does not apply to:
  (i) Grand jury proceedings, civil proceedings, parole hearings, or administrative cases;
  (ii) Violations of the "knock and announce rule" in executing search warrants;
  (iii) Evidence seized as a result of Miranda violations;
(3) Excluded evidence and impeachment:
  (i) Confessions resulting from Miranda violations or illegally obtained evidence may be used to impeach D's testimony at trial (but only D's testimony);
(4) Govt. good-faith defenses to the exclusionary rule (Illegally obtained evidence will not be excluded if the govt. demonstrates that it relied in good faith on either):
  (i) A reasonably relied upon but defective search warrant;
  (ii) Evidence seized via an invalid warrant obtained in good faith will be excluded in some situations;
  (iii) A judicial opinion or statute that was later changed or declared invalid.

