cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: those in custody must be informed of Miranda rights prior to interrogation; otherwise subsequent statements are inadmissible;
  (i) Miranda only applies when accused is in custody and interrogated;
(3) Custody:
  (i) accused is not free to leave;
(4) Interrogation:
  (i) Statements by police likely to elicit incriminating responses;
  (ii) Unsolicited statements are not protected;
  (iii) Note: routine questioning (e.g., during booking or a probation interview) is not considered interrogation;
  (iv) Public safety exception: police may interrogate suspects without giving Miranda warnings if necessary for public safety (e.g., D has info about a bomb that could go off in public);
(5) Miranda warnings:
  (i) Police must inform accused that he has;
  (ii) A right to remain silent;
  (iii) Anything said can be used against him;
  (iv) He has a right to the presence of an attorney;
  (v) One will be appointed if he cannot afford one;
  (vi) Substantial compliance in reading warnings is sufficient;
  (vii) Failure to give warnings implicates 5th Amend., not 6th Amend.

