cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: An accused may terminate an interrogation at any time by invoking his right to remain silent or by requesting counsel;
  (i) Police must cease all questions;
  (ii) Only the accused can re-initiate dialogue;
  (iii) Police may resume questions after a significant period concerning unrelated crimes;
  (iv) D must be re-warned of Miranda rights;
(3) Invoking 5th Amend. right to counsel:
  (i) Once accused requests counsel unambiguously, police must cease all questions on any topic;
  (ii) Note: different than 6th Amend. right to counsel, which is offense-specific and only attaches once charges are filed;
  (iii) If accused initiates communication, interrogation is allowed;
(4) Waiving Miranda rights:
  (i) Valid Miranda waiver must be;
  (ii)
  (a) knowingly
  (b) voluntarily made;
  (iii) Burden is on prosecution to prove this by preponderance of the evidence;
(5) 14th Amend. & confessions:
  (i) To be admissible, the 14th Amend. Due Process Clause requires that confessions be voluntary;
  (ii) Voluntariness is assessed based on totality of circumstances, including suspect's age, mental/physical condition, education, and the duration, manner, and setting of the interrogation.

