(1) General Rule: D cannot be retried for the same offense once jeopardy has attached. Arises when D is prosecuted with one crime and tried, then charged again based on the same offense; Same offense:
  (i) offenses are different if conviction for one offense requires proof of an element not included in the other offense;
  (ii) Lesser included offense: once jeopardy attaches for the greater offense, D cannot be charged for a lesser included offense;
(3) Examples of Same Offense:
  (i) Same offense: first offense requires proof of A, B, & C; second offense requires proof of A & B; second offense is barred;
  (ii) Different offense: first offense requires proof of A & B; second offense requires proof of A, C, & D;
(4) Exceptions:
  (i) New evidence for greater offense becomes available;
  (ii) D can be tried for battery and subsequently tried for homicide if the victim later dies from the battery;
(5) When jeopardy attaches:
  (i) Start of trial generally required;
  (ii) For Example: does not attach for charges or grand jury proceedings alone;
  (iii) Jury trial: attaches once jury is impanelled and sworn in;
  (iv) Bench trial: attaches once first witness is sworn in;
  (v) Pleas: attaches once court accepts a plea agreement.

