(1) General Rule: Once 6th Amend. right to counsel attaches, police may not elicit incriminating statements outside the presence of D's counsel;
  (i) 5th Amend. right to counsel:
  (a) Not automatic: accused must invoke the right by unambiguously requesting presence of counsel. Applies to any custodial interrogation;
  (b) Not offense-specific: once invoked, police must stop questioning on all subjects;
  (ii) 6th Amend. right to counsel:
  (a) Automatic: attaches once charges have been filed and at all subsequent stages;
  (b) Offense-specific: Police can question D about any other crimes
(5) Right to effective counsel:
  (i) Included in 6th Amend. right to counsel;
  (ii) To establish ineffective assistance of counsel on appeal, D must show there is a reasonable probability that his trial's outcome would have been different absent counsel's deficient performance.

