cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Right to counsel:
  (i) A suspect has a right to counsel at any post-charge, in-person lineup or showup;
  (ii) Does not apply to non-live identification procedures (e.g., photographic lineups, fingerprinting)
  (iii) Lineup: witness is shown several possible suspects;
  (iv) Showup: witness is asked to identify a single suspect;
(2) Due process considerations (D can attack pretrial identification procedures as a denial of due process rights if):
  (i) Identification is unnecessarily suggestive;
  (ii) There is a substantial likelihood of misidentification;
  (iii) Determined under the totality of the circumstances;
  (iv) Tough standard; must be extremely suggestive;
  (v) For Example: perpetrator believed to be male and suspect is the only male in lineup; would likely violate due process;
(3) Remedy for violation:
  (i) D may move to suppress any subsequent in-trial identifications made by the witness;
  (ii) Note: Remedy for a violation is rare b/c govt. can often prove the identifying witness has an independent source of identification to overcome the exclusionary rule.

