cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: A D may enter a plea bargain, but doing so waives his 6th Amend. right to a jury trial; Requirements for valid plea bargain (judge must):
  (i) Determine plea is voluntary and intelligently made;
  (ii) Ensure that D understands:
  (a) Nature of the charge and its critical elements;
  (b) Maximum authorized penalty and any mandatory sentence
  (c) That D has a right to plead not guilty;
  (d) That D is waiving his right to a jury trial;
(3) Appellate courts will not disturb valid pleas unless:
  (i) Plea was made involuntarily (e.g., due to a misunderstanding);
  (ii) The court that took the plea lacked jurisdiction;
  (iii) D had ineffective assistance of counsel;
  (iv) The prosecutor failed to honor the plea;
(4) Contract theory of plea bargaining:
  (i) Pleas will be enforced against both parties, but the judge is not required to accept or adhere to the agreement;
  (ii) The prosecutor can threaten D with a more serious crime than he was initially charged with and even follow through on such threats if D does not accept plea.

