cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Govt. has a duty to disclose material exculpatory evidence to D. Failure to disclose violates due process, whether intentional or not. Violation is grounds for reversing conviction; Establishing violation (D must show):
  (i) Evidence impeaches or is exculpatory;
  (ii) Evidence is favorable to D;
  (iii) Prejudice has resulted: will be found if there is a reasonable probability the result of the case would have been different if the undisclosed evidence had been presented at trial.
(3) Applicability of duty to disclose:
  (i) Applies to evidence relevant to prosecution's case in chief;
  (ii) Duty does not apply to post-conviction proceedings.

