cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: 6th Amend. provides right to a jury trial for all "serious offenses." D has a right to be present for all critical stages (e.g., jury selection).
(2) Serious offense: Potential imprisonment for more than 6 months; Jury size and selection requirements:
  (i) Jury size and unanimity: jury must contain at least 6 jurors; unanimous verdict is required for all serious offenses;
  (ii) Juror composition requirements: the jury pool ("venire") must be a representative cross-section of the community. The chosen jury does not have to be representative;
  (iii) Right to an impartial jury: D can question potential jurors on possible prejudices if relevant to the case (e.g., racial biases, feelings on the death penalty); jurors can be struck for cause if their views would prevent or substantially impair them from performing their duties;
  (iv) Peremptory challenges: parties may exercise peremptory challenges for any reason;
  (v) Peremptory Challenge Exception: cannot be used to exclude jurors on account of race or gender (violates equal protection);
(4) Judge cannot direct a verdict of guilt:
  (i) deprives D of his right to a jury trial (but judge may direct a verdict of acquittal).

