cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: The 14th Amend. Due Process Clause requires that the govt. prove guilt beyond a reasonable doubt in all criminal cases; Proving guilt beyond a reasonable doubt:
  (i) Prosecution must prove all elements of every crime charged beyond a reasonable doubt;
  (ii) Burden is always on the prosecution: this cannot be changed; for example, a state law shifting burden onto D to prove he is not guilty is unconstitutional;
  (iii) D has burden of proving any affirmative defenses he raises;
  (iv) State laws vary on what burden D must satisfy (i.e., there is no single constitutional requirement);
  (v) A conviction is valid unless no rational judge or jury, viewing evidence in the light most favorable to prosecution, would convict D.
(3) Jury instructions & mandatory presumptions:
  (i) Judge cannot give mandatory jury instructions on elements of a charged crime;
  (ii) Requiring jury to make a presumption regarding an element of the charged crime violates due process;
  (iii) For Example: in murder trial where body was never found, cannot instruct jury to presume that a missing person is presumed dead.

