cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Similar occurrences: evidence of prior similar occurrences concerning the time, event, or person in the present controversy is often inadmissible as irrelevant or as presenting an unfair risk of prejudice; however, similar occurrences may be relevant for other purposes.
(2) Admissible uses (similar occurrences may be admissible to prove):
(1) Causation; Prior accidents demonstrating
  (i) A pattern of fraudulent claims;
  (ii) Pre-existing conditions;
(3) Intent or absence of mistake; To rebut a defense of impossibility; Value (e.g., similar transactions can establish value); Industry custom (e.g., to prove standard of care); and
(7) Business routine (e.g., to show that a particular event occurred);
  (i) a person's habit may be relevant and admissible to show that the person acted in conformity with that habit on a given occasion;
  (ii) Conduct must be highly specific and frequently repeated (i.e., a person's regular response to a specific set of circumstances);
  (iii) Look for regular, instinctive, habitual conduct. E.g., evidence that a person habitually goes down a particular stairwell two steps at a time could be admissible as circumstantial evidence that she did so at the time in question.

