cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Defense: may introduce evidence of pertinent good character. Must be pertinent to the charged crime (e.g., D's reputation for peacefulness is irrelevant to a forgery charge);
  (i) Method: D may call W to testify to D's good character based on reputation or opinion (but not specific instances);
  (ii) P's rebuttal: once D "opens the door," P may rebut by
  (a) Cross-ex of D's character W (including knowledge of specific instances of D's misconduct or prior arrests);
  (b) Calling W to testify to D's bad character (limited to D's character for the trait in question;
(2) Prosecution: may not initiate introduction of character evidence about D (i.e., can't "open the door"), except:
  (i) Sexual assault/child molestation cases: P can offer evidence of D's other acts of sexual assault or child molestation;
  (ii) If D first offers evidence of victim's character: P can offer evidence that D has the same character trait;
  (iii) Direct: reputation and opinion evidence is admissible; evidence of specific instances is inadmissible;
  (iv) Cross: reputation, opinion, and specific instances are admissible

