cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Extrinsic evidence:
  (i) Any evidence other than W's testimony at the current proceeding;
  (ii) Includes evidence of out-of-court prior inconsistent statements;
  (iii) Extrinsic evidence of contradictory facts is generally admissible to impeach W on material, non-collateral matters;
(2) Collateral matter (a fact not material to issues in the case):
  (i) Says nothing about W's credibility; only used to contradict; For Example: W1 testifies he was headed to the store when he saw D commit murder; defense cannot call W2 to testify that W1 was really headed to see his mistress. This is collateral (i.e., not material) to the issue of what W1 saw;
  (ii) Test (to determine if evidence is collateral, ask): would the evidence be material to the given issue if not for W's contrary assertion? If not, it is likely collateral.

