cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Prior conviction (Felonies not involving dishonesty/false statements):
  (i) If W is the D: admissible if govt. shows probative value outweighs prejudicial effect;
  (ii) If W is non-D: admissible but court can exclude under 403 balancing;
  (iii) Misdemeanors: inadmissible unless it involves dishonesty/false statements;
(2) Prior conviction involving act of dishonesty:
  (i) Always admissible: court has no discretion to exclude under 403 (rare exception; includes felonies and misdemeanors;
  (ii) Acts of dishonesty: prior conviction required proof or admission of an act of dishonesty or false statement (e.g., perjury, fraud);
(3) Convictions more than 10 years old (felonies & misdemeanors):
  (i) Not admissible, unless: Probative value substantially outweighs unfair prejudice (note – inverse of 403 balancing) and adverse party is given notice;
  (ii) Determining 10-year date: more than 10 years must have elapsed since date of conviction or date of release from confinement, whichever is later.

