cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Witness competency: testifying witnesses must be competent, meaning they must satisfy requirements of basic reliability. Witnesses are generally presumed to be competent; Competency qualifications (to be competent, W must have):
  (i) Personal knowledge: W's testimony must be based on her own perceptions (e.g., what W saw or heard);
  (ii) Memory: W must have the ability to remember (e.g., must not have amnesia);
  (iii) Communication: W must be able to relay her perceptions, either directly or through an interpreter;
  (iv) Sincerity: W must take an oath or affirm to tell the truth
  (v) Diminution of any of the above capacities usually goes only to the weight of testimony (i.e., makes W less persuasive).
(3) Excluding witnesses: upon a party's request, the court must order witnesses excluded from hearing other witnesses' testimony; does not apply to parties or party representatives (e.g., where party is a non-person entity).

