cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Present recollection refreshed (use of documents to refresh W's memory during testimony):
  (i) Anything can be used to refresh W's memory;
  (ii) W cannot read aloud from a document, but can look at it briefly, then continue testimony unassisted;
  (iii) Opponent may inspect and offer into evidence anything used to refresh W's memory;
  (iv) Document is not read into evidence (distinguish from recorded recollection);
(2) Recorded recollection (contents of a record/document W previously made or adopted is read into evidence):
  (i) Requirements:
  (a) W once had personal knowledge of the record's subject matter;
  (b) W's memory is insufficient to testify as to the record's contents (i.e., present recollection refreshed was ineffective);
  (c) Record was made or adopted by W when the matter was fresh in W's memory;
  (d) Record accurately reflects W's knowledge;
  (ii) Note: recorded recollection is a hearsay exception; as such it may be admitted in to evidence (distinguish from present recollection refreshed).

