cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Form of question objections:
  (i) Calls for narrative: non-specific, open-ended question that allows witness to tell a story rather than give specific testimony in response to specifically asked questions;
  (ii) Leading: question itself suggests the answer; improper on direct unless witness is hostile or an adverse party; acceptable on cross-exam;
  (iii) Assumes facts not in evidence: question makes an assumption which has not been established on the record;
  (iv) Argumentative: a question that is not designed or intended to elicit relevant facts, but rather is an argumentative assertion;
  (v) Compound: question that asks more than one question at a time; attorneys must ask questions individually;
  (vi) Beyond scope of direct: arises on cross-exam. Attorneys must confine their questions during cross-exam to the scope of direct (i.e., they cannot ask questions involving matters not discussed on direct);
(2) Testimonial objections:
  (i) Unresponsive/nonresponsive: witness's testimony does not relate to or directly answer the question asked; Note: these objections must be specific and promptly made; otherwise they are deemed waived.

