cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Lay opinion requirements (opinion testimony is admissible if it is):
  (i) Rationally based: opinion is rationally based on W's perception;
  (ii) Helpful: opinion is helpful to the trier of fact; it gives the jury more information regarding W's perception than the perception alone; legal conclusions are inadmissible because they are deemed unhelpful;
  (iii) Not expert: not based on scientific, technical, or other specialized knowledge (i.e., not in the realm of expert opinion);
(1) Examples of admissible lay opinion testimony:
  (i) Speed of a car;
  (ii) Emotional state of an individual;
  (iii) Voice or handwriting recognition;
  (iv) Sense recognition;
  (v) Intoxication.

