cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Expert opinion requirements (expert testimony is admissible if):
  (i) Helpful: expert opinion must be helpful to the trier of fact; expert uses specialized knowledge to reach conclusions an average juror would not reach alone;
  (ii) Qualified: expert must possess special knowledge, skill, experience, training, or education;
  (iii) Reasonable certainty: expert must believe in her opinion to a reasonable degree of certainty;
  (iv) Proper factual basis: opinion must be based on facts; expert may base opinion on admitted evidence, personal knowledge, or inadmissible evidence properly relied upon (e.g., data, other testimony, experience);
  (v) Reliable principals reasonably relied upon:
  (a) Scientific evidence: if expert opinion is based on science, court also considers whether evidence is
(1) Peer tested and capable of retesting;
(2) Published;
(3) Has a low error rate;
(4) Reasonably accepted in the field of study.

