cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Fed. courts recognize several testimonial privileges:
  (i) There are no FRE privilege rules;
  (ii) Fed. courts have created and adopted these privileges;
  (iii) State privilege rules (which often vary) apply in fed. cases based on diversity jurisdiction.
(1) Testimonial privileges:
  (i) Attorney-client;
  (ii) Clergy-penitent;
  (iii) Spousal;
  (iv) Marital communications;
  (v) Psychotherapist/social worker-patient;
  (vi) Governmental;
(2) Self-incrimination (under 5th Amend., W cannot be compelled to provide self-incriminating testimony in either civil or criminal cases):
  (i) W may invoke privilege if there is a reasonable possibility of self-incrimination;
  (ii) Civil cases: jury may draw an adverse inference from W's assertion of 5th Amend. privilege;
  (iii) Criminal cases: D cannot be punished for invoking privilege;

