cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Communications between an attorney and client or client's representatives are privileged in all proceedings unless waived:
  (i) Organizational clients: privilege applies to any employee authorized to speak to the attorney;
(2) To be protected, a communication must be:
  (i) Intended to be confidential;
  (ii) Made to facilitate legal services;
(3) Exceptions (privilege does not apply to):
  (i) Crime or fraud: privilege does not apply if a client seeks legal services to aid in the planning or commission of a fraud or a crime;
  (ii) Attorney defending malpractice claim: privilege does not apply if communication relates to an alleged breach of the attorney's duty.
(4) Joint representation of parties in a lawsuit:
  (i) no privilege;
  (ii) where an attorney acts for both parties in a transaction, no privilege can be invoked in a lawsuit between the parties;
  (iii) but privilege can be claimed in a suit between either or both of the parties and a third person.
(5) Fees not covered:
  (i) records of fee payments, including fee arrangements and payments, are generally considered outside (i.e., not covered by) attorney-client privilege.

