cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Physician-patient privilege:
  (i) prevents disclosure of information confidentially conveyed by a patient to a physician;
  (ii) statutory privilege not recognized in FRE, but recognized and applied in most fed. courts on the basis of state law;
(2) To be protected, communication must be:
  (i) Made for purposes of obtaining diagnosis or treatment;
  (ii) Pertinent to diagnosis or treatment;
  (iii) Intended by the patient to be confidential;
(3) Exception (privilege does not apply where):
  (i) Patient's condition is a legal issue (e.g., personal injury);
  (ii) Physician's services were sought to aid in a crime, tort, or to escape capture;
  (iii) Dispute between doctor and patient (e.g., malpractice);
(4) Psychotherapist/social worker-patient privilege (Material conveyed by patient is privileged in all civil or criminal cases if):
  (i) Client intends the communication to be confidential;
  (ii) Communication is made to facilitate therapy or social work; in most ways, this privilege operates similar to attorney-client privilege.

