(1) Every item of physical evidence must be authenticated (meaning, the proponent must show that the evidence is what he claims it is):
  (i) Proving authentication: may be proved by any means that serve to establish authenticity (low burden); For Example: item may be compared with already-authenticated item;
  (ii) Self-authenticating evidence: writings that contain identifying information do not need separate authentication. For Example: deeds, notarized documents, newspapers;
(2) Authentication issues:
  (i) Ancient documents (automatically authenticated if):
  (a) 20 or more years old;
  (b) Does not present any irregularities on its face;
  (c) Found in a place of natural custody;
  (ii) Photos: must have personal knowledge to authenticate; does fact testified to equal the fact perceived?;
  (iii) Voice: whether heard firsthand or through a recording, a voice may be identified by anyone who heard the voice at any time;
  (iv) Non-unique items:
  (a) item facially indistinguishable from others of its kind (e.g., bag of white powder, generic syringe);
  (b) Proponent must establish "chain of custody," that the proffered evidence is the same item it is claimed to be (will be admissible absent large breaks in chain).

