cards.backMarkdown:
(1) "Writing": any tangible collection of data (e.g., videos, documents, photos, books, e-mails, text messages, computer drives, x-rays);
(2) Applicability: rule only applies if evidence is offered to prove its contents (e.g., W's knowledge is obtained from a writing, case turns on contents of a legal instrument, etc.);
(3) Evidence sufficient to prove a writing's contents:
  (i) Originals;
  (ii) Duplicates: must be a machine or carbon copy; admissible unless there is a genuine question as to the authenticity of the original itself;
  (iii) Testimony regarding contents: admissible if original is lost or destroyed, unless done so in bad faith by proponent of testimony;
  (iv) Voluminous documents exception: a voluminous series of documents may be summarized in court; originals relied upon must be available for inspection;
(4) Completeness doctrine: if a party introduces part of a writing or record into evidence, an adverse party may introduce evidence that should be fairly considered with it.

