cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Judicially-noticeable facts:
  (i) Manifest facts: those capable of verification by a source that is not subject to reasonable dispute;
  (ii) Notorious facts: those generally known within the jurisdiction;
(2) Judicial notice of laws:
  (i) Court must take judicial notice of fed. and state laws and regulations;
  (ii) All other laws, court has discretion to take judicial notice (For Example: municipal ordinances, foreign laws, etc.);
(3) Effect of judicially-noticed facts/laws:
  (i) Civil: jury must take judicially-noticed facts as conclusive;
  (ii) Criminal: jury may take judicially-noticed facts as conclusive, but is not required to;
(4) Judicial testimony: a presiding judge can not testify as a witness at trial (i.e., no party can call the trial judge to testify).

