cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Common non-hearsay out-of-court statements:
  (i) Statements of independent legal significance:
  (a) statement contains legally operative words;
  (b) not hearsay b/c offered to show that the statement was said, not whether it was true;
  (c) For Example: in a contract dispute, A testifies that B told him it was a "done deal";
  (ii) Statements offered to show their effect on the listener or reader:
  (a) For Example: in a negligence claim, a statement warning P of the injury-causing condition is admissible to show notice to P;
  (iii) Statements offered to show speaker's knowledge:
  (a) For Example: D, charged with conspiracy claims he did not know about the crime; statement indicating D was told specifics of the crime will be admissible, indicating he knew it was planned;
  (iv) Statements offered to show state of mind:
  (a) Statements offered as circumstantial evidence of declarant's state of mind are not hearsay;
  (b) For Example: statement by D, before running into traffic and causing accident, that he is invisible may be used to show insanity;
  (c) Compare with state of mind hearsay exception, which allows hearsay statements that reflect directly (not circumstantially) on declarant's state of mind.

