cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Statement of party-opponent:
  (i) out-of-court statements by a party are admissible if offered against that party;
  (ii) Judicial statements: made in pleading or testimony
  (iii) Adoptive statement: acquiescence in another's statement;
  (iv) Silence: can be a statement/admission if:
  (a) Party heard, understood, and was capable of responding;
  (b) Reasonable person in the party's position would have responded;
(2) Vicarious statement:
  (i) statement by someone other than the person against whom the statement is offered;
  (ii) Agency: statement by agent/employee on matters within scope of agency/employment is admissible against principal;
  (iii) Authorized speaker: statement by one authorized by a party to speak on her behalf is admissible against the party;
  (iv) Co-conspirator: co-conspirator's statements are admissible against D if made in furtherance of conspiracy.
(3) Declarant-W's prior statement (a prior statement by a declarant who testifies and is subject to cross-examination is admissible where the statement is either):
  (i) Inconsistent with declarant's testimony and given under oath;
  (ii) Prior consistent statement: admissible to rebut charge of fabrication, improper motive or influence, or rehabilitate credibility;
  (iii) Prior statement of identification after perception: admissible to identify a person as someone declarant perceived earlier.

