cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Declarant must be unavailable for these exceptions to apply:
  (i) Former testimony*;
  (ii) Statements against interest*;
  (iii) Dying declarations*;
  (iv) Statements of personal or family history;
  (v) Statements offered against party procuring declarant's unavailability.
(2) "Unavailability":
  (i) refers to declarant's testimony;
  (ii) For Example: a declarant can be in court, but her testimony is "unavailable" because she asserts a valid privilege;
  (iii) Declarant is unavailable if either:
  (a) Privilege (exempt from testifying due to a privilege);
  (b) Death or physical/mental sickness;
  (c) Refusal to testify despite a court order;
  (d) Lack of memory;
  (e) Absent (beyond reach of court's subpoena power and the statement's proponent has not been able to procure attendance or testimony).

