cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Statement of then-existing state of mind:
  (i) Usually offered to show a declarant's intent at the time the statement was made or as a circumstantial inference that declarant's intent was likely carried out;
  (ii) Distinguish from statements offered as circumstantial evidence of declarant's state of mind, which are not hearsay;
  (iii) Statements of intent may be admissible as circumstantial evidence tending to show that an act was committed at a later time;
(2) Statement of then-existing condition:
  (i) Usually offered to establish some physical condition, symptom, or sensation that declarant experienced at the time of the statement.
(1) statement must concern a then-existing condition or mental state;
(2) statements of memory or belief are inadmissible b/c they do not reflect on a then-existing condition.

