cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Requirements (hearsay statements in the form of business records are admissible if they are):
  (i) A record or transaction made or recorded by a business (For Example: receipts, reports, patient records);
  (ii) Made in the regular course of business (i.e., regular practice);
  (iii) Made by someone with knowledge at or near the time of the matters described;
  (iv) Authenticated or certified in writing:
  (a) Trustworthiness: court may exclude an otherwise qualifying record if circumstances indicate a lack of trustworthiness;
  (b) Absence of record: records meeting these requirements may be admitted to show that a matter did not occur or exist;
(2) Police reports: in criminal cases, police reports or other criminal investigative reports are inadmissible against the defendant as business records or public records;
  (i) business records often involve multiple layers of hearsay;
  (ii) every layer must fall into some exception or exemption to be admissible;
  (iii) For Example: minutes of a business meeting with a secretary's notes of participants' statements; secretary's notes are one level of hearsay, and participants' statements are another.

