cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Limitations on marriage:
  (i) Age: most states impose a minimum age requirement, usually 18, before a person can consent to marriage; some states allow minors to marry if there is parental consent or judicial approval;
  (ii) Consanguinity: people who are too closely related are prohibited from marrying each other;
  (iii) Capacity: each party must have the ability to comprehend and voluntarily consent to the marriage;
  (iv) Physical capacity: in many states, marriage is voidable if one party is physically unable to consummate the marriage and the other party was unaware of the physical condition;
  (v) Bigamy/polygamy: no person may marry who has a prior undissolved marriage to another living spouse;
  (a) Exceptions:
(1) Removal of impediment: under the Uniform Marriage & Divorce Act ("UMDA"), a bigamous marriage can be validated upon the removal of the impediment (i.e., when the prior marriage is terminated);
(2) Presumption of validity: under the presumption of validity, the last of several marriages is presumed valid, which may be rebutted by evidence that the prior marriage(s) still persist.

