cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: In a common law marriage, a couple is legally considered married without having registered or performed legal requirements for marriage; abolished in most states; Requirements (where recognized, a common law marriage is established by):
  (i) Consent — exchange of consent between two people; must be consent to be in a permanent, exclusive relationship; agreement to cohabitate alone is insufficient;
  (ii) Cohabitation;
  (iii) Holding out publicly as spouses living together: for example, joint bank account, same last name, telling people they are married;
(3) Recognition: though largely abolished, if a valid common law marriage is formed under one state's laws, it is regarded as a valid marriage in other states, even those where common law marriage is illegal.

