cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Before and during marriage, each spouse owns and controls their own property, but property acquired during marriage may become owned as tenancy by the entirety;
  (i) Tenancy by the entirety: in many states, where spouses take real property jointly, a tenancy by the entirety is presumptively created; if marriage is dissolved, parties hold property as tenants in common;
  (ii) Support: each spouse has an obligation to support the other, and one spouse may be held liable for another spouse's purchases; under agency principles, one spouse can be held liable to third parties for purchases made by the other spouse where expressly or impliedly authorized;
  (iii) Necessaries doctrine: one spouse may be held liable to creditors for necessaries purchased by the other spouse. For Example: food, medical care, shelter, clothing, etc.

