cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: When property is divided upon marriage dissolution, there are two main approaches used, depending on the state;
  (i) Equitable division of marital property: each spouse takes their separate property and the court divides property acquired during marriage on an equitable basis; most popular approach—assume this approach for MEE purposes unless provided otherwise;
  (ii) Community property: property acquired during the marriage is 50-50 by each spouse, unless acquired by gift or bequest then it is considered separate property;
  (iii) Approach to property division (courts will do the following):
  (a) Categorize property: classify property as marital or separate;
  (b) Determine equitable distribution of marital property: distributed between spouses based on relevant factors;
  (iv) Modification: property distribution decrees are generally not modifiable in most states.

