cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Separate property (generally includes):
  (i) Before marriage: property acquired before marriage by either spouse;
  (ii) By gift or bequest: property acquired by gift, bequest, devise, or descent (i.e., family money) during marriage by either spouse;
  (iii) Separate property proceeds: property acquired with separate property proceeds by either spouse;
  (iv) Appreciation b/c of time: appreciation of separate property due to passage of time (as opposed to efforts of either spouse);
(2) Marital property (generally includes all property acquired during marriage that is not separate property, regardless of who holds title):
  (i) Appreciation b/c of effort: appreciation of separate property due to efforts of either spouse is usually marital property;
  (ii) Pensions: portion earned by one spouse during marriage is considered marital property;
  (iii) Professional license or degree: in some states reimbursement may be ordered if one spouse provided support that contributed to the other spouse's degree or license;
(3) Commingled property: separate property that is inextricably mingled with marital property or separate property of the other spouse can become marital property.

