cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Guidelines & formulas:
  (i) Each state has guidelines to determine the proper amount of child support owed;
  (ii) Guidelines are usually based on a formula that considers number of children, their ages, healthcare needs, any special needs, and parents' incomes;
  (iii) Time share (how much time the children live with each parent) is also a factor;
(2) Duration: child support obligations generally last until the child reaches the age of majority or is otherwise emancipated;
(3) Independent from visitation rights: custodial parents cannot deny visitation rights based on a parent's failure to make child support payments;
(4) Jurisdiction:
  (i) Full faith and credit is given to child support orders issued in other states as long as the issuing court had proper jx and the parties had reasonable notice and an opportunity to be heard;
  (ii) The issuing court has continuing exclusive jx to modify the order if the child or one of the parties resides in-state (unless parties have moved out of state but consent to the issuing court's ongoing jx).

