cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Types of custody:
  (i) Legal custody: right to make major decisions affecting the child's life;
  (ii) Physical custody: possession and control of the child;
  (iii) Joint custody: can be either or both of:
  (a) Parents share decision-making but child lives with one parent;
  (b) Child divides time between each parent's home
(2) Custody factors (in determining custody, courts focus on the child's best interests, looking at multiple factors, including):
  (i) Parents' wishes;
  (ii) Child's wishes (given more weight if child is older, but significantly less weight for young children, i.e., under age eight);
  (iii) Ability and willingness of each parent to provide for child's needs;
  (iv) Interaction and interrelationship of child with parents, siblings, and others who affect the child's best interests;
  (v) Child's adjustment to home, school, and community;
(3) Visitation:
  (i) When one parent is granted sole physical custody, the other parent is entitled to visitation;
  (ii) Exception: visitation rights may be denied if court determines it would endanger the child's wellbeing;
  (iii) Non-parents: may be given visitation rights if:
  (a) The non-parent has a substantial relationship with the child;
  (b) Non-parent visitation is in the child's best interests;
  (c) Fact finder must give special consideration to the wishes of fit parents regarding visitation rights.

