cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Once a court enters a decree regarding spousal support, child support, or child custody, the decree generally is only modifiable upon a showing of a significant change in circumstances;
  (i) Significant change in circumstance required: standards differ slightly for each, but if modification arises on the exam, look for and note any significant change in circumstances;
(2) Spousal support:
  (i) Changing a support award requires a substantial, material, and unanticipated change in either party's circumstances;
  (ii) Self-induced changes: generally will not justify modifying a support order (e.g., party cannot voluntarily take a lower-paying job and get reduced support obligations);
(3) Child support:
  (i) Child support orders are modifiable based on a substantial change in circumstances that affects either:
  (a) The needs of the children,
  (b) The ability of the parent to pay;
  (ii) Self-induced changes: same rules as for spousal support;
(4) Child custody:
  (i) Modification of a child custody order requires the parent to show a substantial, material change in circumstances;
  (ii) Courts will not change a custody order unless the change is in the child's best interests.

