(1) General Rule: unmarried cohabitants do not have any special status by virtue of living together, unless they satisfy requirements for a common law marriage;
  (i) Ks between unmarried cohabitants to share property or engage in other forms of economic sharing are valid;
  (ii) Exception: where sexual services is the sole consideration supporting the K, it will be invalid;
(3) Implied Ks:
  (i) Courts may allow unmarried cohabitants to seek a remedy based on an implied-in-fact K theory (i.e., K formed by parties' conduct);
  (ii) Court may construe an arrangement as a joint venture, constructive trust, or partnership;
(4) Division of property (where unmarried cohabitants break up, courts may grant an equitable distribution of property based on rehabilitative alimony or one of the following theories):
  (i) Resulting trust: party makes claim to property in another's name; party seeking resulting trust must have paid money to acquire the property with intent to retain an ownership interest;
  (ii) Constructive trust: imposed to prevent a party from being unjustly enriched by obtaining title through wrongful conduct; or
  (iii) Quantum meruit: recovery in quasi-K for valuable services; claim seeks another to pay the fair market value of services rendered to avoid unjust enrichment.

cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Discrimination:
  (i) Distinctions based on non-marital child status are almost always unconstitutional;
  (ii) Note: if you see any exam question where a child is denied benefits or rights (e.g., child support, govt. benefits, inheritance) due to their non-marital child status, it is likely invalid;
(2) Establishing paternity:
  (i) A paternity suit may be brought to establish a non-marital child's biological parent;
  (ii) Often brought by child or mother for the purpose of obtaining support from child's father;
  (iii) Once paternity is established, a duty of support attaches;
  (iv) Additionally, father may seek visitation and custody rights;
(3) Admissible evidence (in paternity actions, evidence may include):
  (i) Blood or genetic tests, which parties may be required to take;
  (ii) Prior statements regarding paternity by deceased family;
  (iii) Medical testimony about a father's sterility and/or probability of paternity based on time elapsed between birth and sex;
  (iv) Admissions or acknowledgments by alleged parent.

