cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: An adoption terminates the legal relationship between biological parents and their child (if not already terminated) and establishes a new legal relationship between parent and child;
  (i) Consent of both biological parents generally required;
  (ii) Unwed father's consent may not be necessary if he has not assumed parental responsibility;
  (iii) But an unwed father considered fit to be a parent has a constitutional right to have an opportunity to develop a quality relationship with his infant child;
  (iv) Consent of adoptee: may be required for prospective adoptees over a certain age (usually 12);
(3) Withdrawal of biological parent consent:
  (i) Not allowed after adoption;
  (ii) Before an adoption decree is entered, withdrawal may be allowed if court determines it is in the adoptee's best interests;
(4) Payment prohibited:
  (i) Most states prohibit adopting parents from paying money to biological parents beyond pregnancy-related medical expenses (i.e., it is illegal to buy and sell children).

