cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Donors:
  (i) One who produces sperm or an egg used for reproduction generally does not have parental rights in a conceived child;
  (ii) Mother's husband is generally presumed to be the father of a child born from artificial insemination;
  (iii) Most states extinguish parental rights of sperm or egg donors;
  (iv) Exception: donors may have parental rights if agreed to in writing by donor and parent(s);
(2) Surrogacy (a.k.a. "gestational agreement"):
  (i) Where a woman agrees to bear a child conceived through assisted reproduction (i.e., using intended parents' eggs or sperm or both) for the intended parents;
  (ii) Agreement: surrogate, surrogate's husband (if she is married), and intended parents enter into a written agreement in which surrogate relinquishes her rights and duties as a parent;
  (iii) Most states allow surrogacy in some form and treat the agreement as a K.

