cards.backMarkdown:
(1) No formalities required: no formal agreement is required; parties' intent to associate as co-owners can be inferred from their conduct;
(2) Proving a partnership exists (questions may address whether a partnership has been formed given the parties' relationship):
  (i) Parties' intent: where parties intended to carry on a business as co-owners, a partnership is formed regardless of whether they intended to be in a partnership;
  (ii) Other factors (where parties' intent is unclear, courts look at):
  (a) Profit-sharing: persons who receive a share of a business's profits are presumed to be partners in the business; exceptions are profits received as payment of a debt, rent, wages, services rendered, etc. (i.e., payment is for a business expense, not a profit distribution);
  (b) Lesser factors: the following factors may also be examined, but their existence does not create a presumption of partnership formation:
(1) sharing of control,
(2) capital investment;
(3) joint ownership of property;
(3) Partnership by estoppel: where no partnership exists, parties may be held liable to third parties as a partnership if they actively held themselves or others out as partners or consented to being held out as partners.

