cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Dissociation (any partner ceasing to be associated in carrying on the partnership business):
  (i) Cause: can be due to departing partner's desire to withdraw, the happening of an agreed-upon event, valid expulsion of the partner, bankruptcy of the partner, etc.;
  (ii) Effect: terminates dissociated partner's legal relationship with partnership, including rights to profits and management rights; dissociating partner's fiduciary duties terminate except regarding matters occurring prior to the dissociation;
  (iii) Buying out: if partnership continues, it must purchase the dissociated partner's interest;
(2) Dissolution (termination of partnership):
  (i) Cause: happening of an agreed-upon event, expiration of a term in the partnership agreement, issuance of judicial decree, etc. In an at-will partnership (i.e., one formed with no specific undertaking or definite term), any partner can dissolve at any time by providing a notice of dissolution;
  (ii) Winding up:
  (a) upon dissolution, partnership must wind up business activities and distribute assets;
  (b) partnership continues until winding up is complete;
  (c) distributing assets occurs once assets are reduced to cash, liabilities are paid first to creditors, then partners individually.

