cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A fee simple in which grantor retains the power to terminate grantee's estate upon the happening of a given event or condition;
  (i) Forfeiture not automatic: if the event or condition occurs, grantee still retains title until grantor exercises his reentry right; this is what distinguishes fee simple subject to condition subsequent from a fee simple determinable;
  (ii) Potentially infinite: duration can be infinite so long as the event or condition does not occur;
  (iii) Transferable: alienable, devisable, and descendible, subject to the occurrence of the given event or condition;
(2) Creation: clear durational language must carve out a right of reentry for grantor; it must be explicit that grantor has the right to retake upon occurrence of the event or condition; words of desire, hope, or aspiration are insufficient; Accompanying future interest is a right of reentry: grantor retains right of reentry.

