cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A fee simple that automatically transfers to a third party upon the happening of a given event or condition; For Example: "To A, but if A is ever arrested, then to B"; Characteristics:
  (i) Automatic forfeiture: upon occurrence of the event or condition, estate automatically transfers to a third person; similar to a fee simple determinable, but ownership automatically transfers to a third person, not grantor;
  (ii) Potentially infinite: duration can be infinite so long as the event or condition does not occur;
  (iii) Transferable: alienable, devisable, and descendible, subject to the occurrence of the event or condition;
  (iv) Absolute restraints on alienation are void;
(2) Creation: clear durational language is required; words of desire, hope, or aspiration are insufficient; Accompanying future interest is a shifting executory interest: the third party holds the shifting executory interest; it is transferable and the third party's interest is alienable, devisable, and descendible.

