cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An interest that lasts only for the life of the interest holder; For Example: O grants "to A for life"; A has a life estate and is the life tenant (LT) until she dies;
(2) Defeasibility:
  (i) Can be defeasible like fee estates (for example, determinable, subject to condition or executory interest) or indefeasible;
  (ii) LT has all ownership rights but must maintain property and make reasonable repairs;
  (iii) LT cannot commit waste;
(3) Accompanying future interest is a reversion or remainder:
  (i) Reversion: future interest in grantor when a life estate does not provide for disposition of property to a third party; For Example: O "to A for life"; A is the LT, O has a reversion;
  (ii) Remainder: future interest following a life estate that identifies a third person; For Example: O "to A for life, then to B"; A is the LT, B has a remainder;
(4) Life estate pur autre vie (p.a.v.):
  (i) Life estate measured by the life of someone other than the LT; For Example: O grants "To A for the life of B"; A is the LT, holding the property until B dies, at which point property reverts back to O;
  (ii) Transfer of life estate: creates a life estate p.v. held by transferee (for example, LT transfers life estate to B; B holds a life estate that reverts to the grantor O when the LT dies).

