cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A life tenant (LT) cannot commit acts that constitute an unreasonable use of land and/or injure the interests of a future interest-holder; doing so constitutes waste, of which there are three types;
  (i) Affirmative (voluntary) waste (LT cannot consume or exploit natural resources on the land except):
  (a) Where necessary for repairs or maintenance of land;
  (b) When grant expressly gives the right to exploit;
  (c) If land was used for exploitation of resources prior to the grant;
  (d) Open mines doctrine: if exploitation occurred before the life estate, LT may only extract from already-open mines;
  (ii) Permissive waste (harm to property due to LT neglect):
  (a) LT has a duty to repair/maintain property up to the extent of income or profits derived from the land or its rental value;
  (b) Includes paying taxes, interest on encumbrances, etc.;
  (c) Future interests holders who assume LT's obligations are entitled to reimbursement;
  (iii) Ameliorative waste:
  (a) LT acts that economically benefit the land;
  (b) Prohibited under common law, but now usually permitted in most modern jurisdictions.

