cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A future interest in a third person (other than grantor) that arises immediately upon the termination of a preceding life estate; For Example: "to A for life, then to B"—A has a life estate, B has a remainder; Characteristics:
  (i) Creation: expressly created in the same conveyance in which the preceding estate is created;
  (ii) Transferable: alienable, devisable, and descendible; cannot cut off or divest an interest held by a prior transferee;
(2) Categories of remainders:
  (i) Vested remainders (three types):
  (a) Indefeasibly vested remainders;
  (b) Vested remainder subject to total divestment;
  (c) Vested remainder subject to open (class gift);
(2) Contingent remainders (arise if):
  (a) There is a condition precedent to the future interest becoming possessory;
  (b) The future interest vests in an unascertained taker;
  (c) Both (a) and (b).

