cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) A remainder that automatically becomes possessory upon the natural expiration of the preceding estate;
  (ii) Limitations: vested remainders cannot
  (a) be subject to any condition precedent,
  (b) vest in an unknown or unascertained person;
(3) Three types of vested remainders:
  (i) Indefeasibly vested remainder: becomes possessory immediately upon termination of the prior estate; For Example: "to A for life, then to B";
  (ii) Vested remainder subject to total divestment: subject to some condition subsequent, such that the remainderman could be divested after taking possession; For Example: "to A for life, remainder to B; but if B weds, to C";
  (iii) Vested remainder subject to open (class gift): remainder vested in a described class of takers, at least one of whom is capable of taking possession (i.e., by virtue of being alive); For Example: "to A for life, remainder to children of B and their heirs"; here, B has one child, who has a vested remainder subject to open (b/c B may have more children);
(4) Open vs. closed class: class stays open to allow for future members and closes when no new members can be created (for example, life tenant dies); Rule of Convenience: class closes whenever any member can call for distribution of her share; after-born class members get nothing.

