cards.backMarkdown:
(1) A remainder will be contingent if it is either:
  (i) Subject to a condition precedent;
  (ii) Created in favor of an unascertained or unborn person;
(2) Subject to condition precedent:
  (i) Remainder's taking is contingent on the prior occurrence of some event or condition;
  (ii) Once the event or condition occurs, the interest automatically becomes an indefeasibly vested remainder;
  (iii) For Example: "to A for life, then to B and his heirs when B gets married";
  (iv) Answer: If B is unmarried at the time of the conveyance, A has a life estate, B has a contingent remainder (b/c marriage is a condition precedent), and grantor has a reversion in case B is not married when A dies; if B gets married he has an indefeasibly vested remainder;
(3) Subject to unborn or unascertained persons:
  (i) A remainder created in favor of unborn or unascertained persons;
  (ii) Remainder is contingent on grantee being born or ascertained;
  (iii) For Example: "to A for life, then to B's heirs";
  (iv) If B is alive, remainder is contingent b/c heirs of B cannot be ascertained until B dies.

