cards.backMarkdown:
  (1) In General: the law has created rules to prevent some consequences that may result from strict application of the estate system's requirements;
Rule of destructibility: Rule of destructibility:
    (i) At common law, a contingent remainder is destroyed if it remains contingent (for example, the condition is not satisfied) when the preceding estate ends;
    (ii) For Example: O grants "to A for life, then to B once he goes to law school"; A dies and B has not gone to law school;
    (iii) At common law, B gets nothing upon A's death;
    (iv) Modern rule: gives a reversion to grantor or grantor's estate until grantee satisfies the condition;
  (3) Merger (Shelley's Rule):
    (i) Arises when a conveyance attempts to give a life estate to grantee with a remainder to grantee's intestate heirs;
    (ii) At common law, the two estates merge;
    (iii) For Example: O grants "to A for life, then to A's heirs" and A is alive; at common law, remainder merges and A has a fee simple absolute;
    (iv) Modern Rule: A has a life estate and his heirs have contingent remainders; O has a reversion b/c A could die without heirs;
  (4) Doctrine of worthier title:
    (i) Arises when grantor creates a life estate in another but creates a future interest in grantor's heirs;
    (ii) For Example: O grants "to A for life, then to O's heirs";
    (iii) Under the doctrine, the contingent remainder in O's heirs is void;
    (iv) A instead has a life estate and O has a reversion.

