cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) A future interest in a third party that takes effect by cutting short some interest;
  (ii) two types: shifting and springing;
  (iii) Includes any future interest that is not a remainder;
  (iv) Executory interest holders lack standing to sue for waste;
  (v) Transferability: devisable, descendible, and usually transferable;
(2) Shifting executory interest:
  (i) Always follows a defeasible fee or vested remainder subject to total divestment;
  (ii) Cuts short someone other than the grantor;
  (iii) For Example: "to A, so long as the property is used for storage. But if used for any other purpose, to B";
  (iv) A has a fee simple subject to an executory interest; B has a shifting executory interest; if A stops using the property for storage, A's interest is cut short (not grantor's);
(3) Springing executory interest:
  (i) Cuts short a present interest held by the grantor or grantor's estate;
  (ii) For Example: "to A, if and when he gets married";
  (iii) A has an executory interest;
  (iv) Grantor has a fee simple subject to an executory interest; if A gets married, possession springs from grantor to A.

