cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An estate with multiple tenants in which each co-tenant owns a distinct, undivided interest and each has a right to possession of the whole estate; Characteristics:
  (i) Freely transferable: each interest is freely descendible, devisable, and alienable; co-tenant interests can be transferred upon death;
  (ii) Rent: a co-tenant can lease his individual interest, which transfers his right of possession to lessee, but co-tenants have a right to share in rents from third-party lessee;
  (iii) No survivorship rights: upon death of a co-tenant, her interest does not pass by law to remaining co-tenants;
  (iv) Partition: a co-tenant may seek judicial partition (i.e., division of property); if not feasible, property may be sold and proceeds apportioned among co-tenants;
  (v) Modern law favors tenancy in common; it is the default concurrent estate.

