cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Creation:
  (i) Four conditions must concurrently exist when the tenants take their interests:
  (a) Time: JTs must take their interests at the same time;
  (b) Title: JTs must receive conveyance through the same instrument;
  (c) Interest: JTs must take equal and identical interests;
  (d) Possession: JTs must have equal possessory rights;
  (ii) Express intent required: grantor must expressly intend to create a JT; otherwise, a tenancy in common is presumed;
  (iii) Right of survivorship: if one JT dies, surviving JTs automatically take equal possession of deceased JT's share;
  (iv) Transferability: alienable, but not devisable or descendible;
(3) Severance & transfer of interests:
  (i) Severance: severance by any JT creates a tenancy in common with respect to the severed interest;
  (ii) Transfer: a JT interest becomes a tenancy in common upon transfer; this does not destroy the entire JT if two or more JTs remain;
  (iii) Mortgage (lien theory (majority) vs. title theory (minority)):
  (a) Lien theory Jx: JT can take a mortgage on her interest without severing JT (b/c no title passes to mortgagee);
  (b) Title theory Jx: JT is severed if any JT takes a mortgage on her interest b/c title passes to the mortgagee.

