cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An estate in which the tenant has a present possessory property interest and the landlord has a future interest (reversion);
(2) Four leasehold estates:
  (i) Tenancy for years:
  (a) Lasts for a fixed period of time;
  (b) Requires a definitive beginning and end date;
  (c) If duration is longer than one year, lease must be in writing (required under SoF);
  (d) Terminates automatically at the end of the fixed period;
  (e) No notice is required;
  (f) Also referred to as "estate for years," "term for years," or "fixed term tenancy."
  (ii) Periodic tenancy: tenancy estate that repeats until terminated;
  (iii) Tenancy at will: Either party can terminate at any time without notice;
  (iv) Tenancy at sufferance: tenant has possession by virtue of wrongfully remaining after termination of a lease (holdover tenant).

