cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Duty to repair (can be largely modified by lease terms):
  (i) Tenant must maintain premises and make ordinary repairs;
  (ii) Residential tenants' duty to repair is modified by the implied warranty of habitability;
(2) Tenant must not commit waste (three types of waste):
  (i) Voluntary: overt, harmful acts (for example, removing fixtures);
  (ii) Permissive: neglect;
  (iii) Ameliorative: alterations increasing property value;
(3) Destruction of premises without fault of landlord or tenant:
  (i) Common law: tenant held liable for any loss;
  (ii) Modern law: tenant can terminate lease;
(4) Duty to pay rent: tenancy at sufferance arises upon breach;
  (i) If tenant uses premises for an illegal purpose, landlord may terminate lease or obtain damages and injunctive relief;
  (ii) Occasional, minor illegal activities do not constitute a breach;
(6) Liability to third parties (in tort): Tenant may be liable for injuries to third persons from the dangerous conditions within the tenant's control.

