cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General:
  (i) Once-movable chattel that is annexed (i.e., affixed) to real property such that it becomes part of the realty;
  (ii) Often arises with leaseholds, but applies to all real property estates;
  (iii) Fixtures pass with ownership of the land;
  (iv) Exception: a life tenant's representative may remove annexed chattel within a reasonable time after life tenant's death;
(2) Determining whether chattel has become a fixture:
  (i) Intent controls: annexor's intent is usually determinative;
  (ii) Fixture almost always arises where annexors affix their own chattel to their own property;
  (iii) Chattel integrated into a structure (for example, heating pipes, bricks built into a wall) almost always becomes a fixture;
(3) Landlord-tenant: agreement between landlord and tenant is controlling, if it exists;
(4) Tenant installation(tenant may remove chattel she installed if):
  (i) Removal occurs before the lease expires;
  (ii) Removal does not cause substantial harm to the property;
(5) Note: If tenant impermissibly removes fixtures, she commits voluntary waste.

