cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Residential property must be fit for basic human dwelling;
  (i) Residential only: not applicable to commercial leases;
  (ii) Absolute duty: cannot be modified by lease terms;
  (iii) Local code or case law: specifies the standard for a breach;
  (iv) For Example: no heat in winter, no plumbing, no water, etc. are types of problems that could give rise to violation of the implied warranty of habitability;
(3) Tenant's remedies (after giving notice to landlord, tenant can):
  (i) Move: vacate premises and terminate the lease;
  (ii) Repair: make reasonable repairs and deduct costs from future rent;
  (iii) Reduce or withhold rent: reduce rent or stop payment until a court determines the fair rental value given the breach; tenant must place withheld rent in escrow;
  (iv) Remain: remain in possession and seek money damages.

