cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A non-possessory property interest that confers a right to use another's land;
  (i) Servient estate: burdened land;
  (ii) Dominant estate: benefited land (not always applicable);
(2) Types of easements:
  (i) Easement appurtenant:
  (a) Entitles a dominant estate owner to use a servient estate's land;
  (b) Attaches to the dominant estate and passes automatically (even if not mentioned in a conveyance);
  (ii) Easement in gross:
  (a) Entitles an individual or entity (not a dominant landowner) to use the servient estate; attaches only to servient estate; there is no dominant estate;
  (b) For Example: right to place a billboard on another's lot, right to run utility line across land, right to fish in another's pond. Similar to a license, but irrevocable; may be transferred;
  (iii) Affirmative easement: entitles its holder to make affirmative use of the servient estate;
  (iv) Negative easement: entitles its holder to restrict the servient estate from otherwise permissible activities;
  (v) Creation: easements may be created by prescription, implication, necessity, or expressly by grant or reservation.

