cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: An easement's scope is determined by the terms or conditions that created it; in interpreting an easement's scope, courts will consider the reasonable intent of the original parties;
(2) Expansion: Easement holders cannot unilaterally expand the scope of their easement (for example, through overuse or misuse); overuse or misuse of an easement does not terminate the easement; remedy for violation is an injunction or damages;
(3) Duty to repair: Easement holder has a duty to make repairs if he is the sole user; if both the servient landowner and the easement holder use an easement, the repair costs are apportioned.

