cards.backMarkdown:
(1) License: a right to use another person's (licensor's) land, which is revocable at the licensor's will; For Example: oral permission for neighbor to use licensor's pool, theater tickets (grant a license to ticket holders), right to use a parking lot;
  (i) Not an interest in land: license is a privilege, not an interest in land (distinguish from affirmative easement);
  (ii) Revocable: licensor may revoke the privilege at any time, unless estoppel applies;
  (iii) Inalienable: may not be assigned or transferred; any attempt to do so revokes the license;
  (iv) No SoF requirement: a license may be oral or written; they can result from easements that are invalid under the SoF; For Example: an oral grant of a permanent easement between neighbors may result in a license b/c SoF not satisfied;
(2) Profit: a non-possessory property interest entitling its holder to enter a servient estate to remove resources; For Example: minerals, timber, soil, fish;
  (i) All rules governing easements apply to profits (i.e., creation, transferability, and termination);
  (ii) Extinguishment: a profit may be extinguished through misuse or overuse of resources on the servient estate.

