cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Equitable conversion:
  (i) During escrow (after land sale K but before deed delivery), buyer owns the real property, but seller owns personal property (i.e., the right to proceeds of the sale);
  (ii) Seller holds legal title in trust for buyer;
  (iii) Action against seller for claims arising before the K: any judgment against seller is converted into an interest in sale proceeds; judgment is not enforceable against real property (i.e., buyer is protected);
(2) Risk of loss:
  (i) Of property is destroyed before closing through no fault of the parties, buyer bears the risk of loss in most jurisdictions;
  (ii) Applies even if buyer has not taken possession;
  (iii) Parties can contract differently;
  (iv) Seller must credit any insurance proceeds from loss against the purchase price;
(3) Death of a party:
  (i) If buyer or seller dies before closing, rights to the contract pass according to interests held;
  (ii) Seller's interest: passes as personal property, and seller's estate can sue for sale proceeds;
  (iii) Buyer's interest: passes as real property, and buyer's estate can sue for delivery.

