cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Every land sale contract contains two implied promises:
  (i) Promise to provide marketable title: promise that title will be free from risk of litigation upon closing;
  (a) Defects rendering title unmarketable:
(1) Acquired by adverse possession; Encumbered by interests (for example, servitude, mortgage, future interest); but seller has the right to satisfy outstanding mortgages or liens with sale proceeds; or
(3) Zoning ordinance violations existing at sale
  (b) Can be waived by buyer (but not seller);
  (ii) Promise to disclose & make no material false statements:
  (a) Seller must not materially misrepresent facts or make false statements concerning the property;
  (b) Seller has a duty to disclose known, latent material defects, which may be disclaimed if disclaimer is clear and specific;
  (c) New property: seller/builder is subject to an implied warranty of quality in construction;
(2) Remedy for breach:
  (i) Buyer must notify seller before closing and give reasonable time for seller to cure defects;
  (ii) If seller fails to cure, buyer can rescind, file for damages, demand specific performance, or file suit to quiet title;
  (iii) Merger: if buyer fails to notify seller before closing, contract merges with the deed and seller is not liable for contractual promises.

