cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General warranty deeds include six covenants for title: Note: these covenants concern condition of title, not condition of the property itself
  (i) Present covenants (only breached at the time of delivery):
  (a) Seisin: grantor covenants that he is the rightful owner (i.e., has title, possession) and that deed covers described land;
  (b) Right to convey: grantor covenants that he has the right to convey;
  (c) Against encumbrances: grantor covenants that the land is free from encumbrances (e.g., servitudes, mortgages);
  (ii) Future covenants (only breached after delivery):
  (a) Quiet enjoyment: grantor covenants that grantee will not be disturbed by a third party's claim of lawful title;
  (b) Warranty: grantor agrees to defend against lawful claims of title by others;
  (c) Further assurances: grantor promises to perform future acts reasonably necessary to perfect the title conveyed.

