cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A BFP is one who purchases property for value (i.e., gives pecuniary consideration) without notice of a prior conveyance; Note: whether a buyer is a BFP is important in the context of recording statutes; Purchasers:
  (i) Includes mortgagees for value;
  (ii) Does not include donees, heirs, or devisees;
  (iii) Not protected by the recording statutes unless the Shelter Rule applies;
(3) Notice (a buyer has notice of a prior conveyance by any of):
  (i) Actual notice: actual knowledge, from any source;
  (ii) Inquiry notice: what a reasonable inspection of the land would reveal (regardless of whether buyer actually inspects);
  (iii) Record notice: knowledge from a routine title search; For Example: a previous conveyance properly recorded in the chain of title (not a wild deed).

