cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Issues that can arise with recording statutes and chain of title:
  (i) Shelter Rule:
  (a) One who takes from a BFP will prevail against any interest the transferor-BFP would have prevailed against, even if the transferee had actual notice of a prior conveyance;
  (b) Protects donees, heirs, or devisees of BFPs who cannot qualify as BFPs and would not otherwise receive protection under notice or race-notice statutes;
  (ii) Wild deeds:
  (a) a recorded deed unconnected to the chain of title (for example, due to a clerk's filing error or the failure to record a prior deed);
  (b) Record notice cannot be derived from a wild deed;
  (c) Wild deed cannot exist in a tract index system
  (iii) Estoppel by deed:
  (a) A grantor who conveys title to land he does not then own is estopped from subsequently acquiring the same land;
  (b) Title automatically passes to the benefit of grantee;
  (c) Prevents one from conveying land they do not presently own and later validly acquiring it (for example, through a will).

