cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Most real property sales are negotiated by real estate brokers:
  (i) Seller's agent ("listing broker"):
  (a) Broker who obtains listing from seller, i.e., engaged by seller to assist in sale of property;
  (b) Has fiduciary duty to seller;
  (c) Earns commission from sale of property once the sale closes;
  (d) Seller's agent may still earn commission if the sale fails to close due to seller's fault (for example, seller backs out);
  (ii) Buyer's agent ("selling broker"):
  (a) Primary relationship is with buyer, for example, shows buyer potential properties buyer may purchase;
  (b) Typically compensated by receiving a portion of listing broker's commission, i.e., gets paid out of seller's agent's commission;
  (c) Common law: owes a fiduciary duty to seller b/c buyer's agent is technically a subagent of the seller's agent;
  (d) Modern statutes: requires separate agreement between buyer's agent and buyer; buyer's agent owes fiduciary duty to buyer but no fiduciary duty to seller;
(2) Duty to disclose: agents have a duty to disclose material information about which they have actual knowledge.

