(1) In General: A mortgage is a security interest in land that serves as collateral for the repayment of a loan (a.k.a. "mortgage deed," "note");
  (i) Writing required: must be in writing to satisfy the SoF;
  (ii) Mortgagor: debtor/borrower/landowner;
  (iii) Mortgagee: creditor;
(2) Parties' rights:
  (i) Lien Theory (majority): mortgagor has title and the right to possession absent foreclosure; mortgagee has a lien, conferring a right to take action for ownership of the land if the mortgagor defaults on the loan;
  (ii) Title theory (minority): mortgagee has title to the property during loan term, not mortgagor-borrower;
  (iii) Intermediate theory (minority): mortgagor has title and right to possession until default occurs per the mortgage; after default mortgagee has title and right to possession;
  (iv) Note: unless instructed otherwise, assume lien theory applies on the MBE;
(3) Equitable mortgage: debtor gives creditor a deed to his land as collateral for the debt (instead of executing a mortgage); Acceleration clauses: terms in loan agreements that require mortgagor to pay off full loan immediately if certain conditions are met, for example, if mortgagor misses too many payments.

