cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Mortgagor transfer:
  (i) Where mortgagor sells property, mortgage remains on the land (i.e., grantee takes subject to the mortgage but is not liable for repayment);
  (ii) Mortgagor remains liable to mortgagee for the loan;
  (iii) Assumption:
  (a) grantee promises to pay existing mortgage loan;
  (b) grantee becomes primarily liable to mortgagee; original party is secondarily liable as surety;
(2) A mortgagee (creditor) can transfer her interest by:
  (i) Endorsing the mortgage note and delivering it to transferee;
  (ii) Executing a separate assignment of the mortgage interest;
(3) Holder in due course:
  (i) A holder in due course lender takes a mortgage note free of any personal defenses mortgagor could have raised against original mortgagee (for example, lack of consideration, fraudulent inducement);
  (ii) He still remains subject to real defenses (e.g., duress, fraud, etc.);
(4) Requirements for holder in due course status:
  (i) Negotiable note: must be made payable to the named mortgagee;
  (ii) Indorsed: note must be signed by the named mortgagee;
  (iii) Delivered: note must be delivered to the transferee;
  (iv) Good faith and value paid: transferee must take the note in good faith (i.e., without notice of illegality) and pay value.

