cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Priority of creditors: creditors must record their interests; recorded interests take priority in the order recorded; Purchase money mortgages (PMM) (superior to all interests):
  (i) PMM: mortgage given in exchange for funds used to buy the property;
  (ii) PMM is given either to the seller as part of the purchase price or to a third-party lender (if both, seller's PMM is senior to the third-party lender);
  (iii) Creditors can agree to subordinate priority to a junior creditor;
(3) Junior interests:
  (i) terminated by foreclosure of a superior claim;
  (ii) Upon foreclosure, junior interest holders cannot look to the land to satisfy debts;
  (iii) Junior interest holders can seek a deficiency judgment against debtor, but they have no interest in the subject property;
  (iv) Necessary parties: junior interests are necessary parties and must be included in a senior foreclosure action; otherwise, the junior interest will remain on the land
(4) Senior interests:
  (i) Unaffected by junior interest foreclosures;
  (ii) Buyer of foreclosed property takes it subject to senior interests;
  (iii) Buyer is not liable for senior debt, but the senior mortgage remains on the land.

