cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Land bordering watercourses (natural or artificial bodies of water; for example, lakes and rivers) is governed by either the riparian doctrine or the prior appropriation doctrine;
  (i) Reasonable use theory (majority): riparian owners share rights to reasonable use and are liable to other owners if their use unreasonably interferes with other owners' use; Balance utility of use vs. gravity of harm;
  (ii) Natural flow theory (minority): riparian owners may be enjoined for any use resulting in a substantial or material reduction in others' water quantity, quality, or velocity;
  (iii) Under both theories, natural uses (e.g., household use) prevail over artificial uses (e.g., for manufacturing or irrigation);
(3) Prior appropriation doctrine: water rights are originally acquired by actual use; priority of beneficial use determines rights to water; For Example: first individual to make a beneficial use of water (i.e., productive use) has superior legal right to its use.

