cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Groundwater: water beneath the surface not confined to a known channel (e.g., water in wells);
  (i) Different states use different approaches — most common are:
  (a) Reasonable use (used in many eastern states);
  (b) Prior appropriation (used in many western states);
(2) Surface water:
  (i) Water from rain, springs, or other runoff that has not yet reached a natural watercourse; landowners can generally use surface water as they please, but may be liable for interrupting its flow in a way that impacts other owners;
  (ii) Liability depends on which theory applies:
  (a) Natural flow theory: owners cannot unreasonably alter natural drainage;
  (b) Common enemy theory: owners can do anything to change drainage or combat flow unless it causes unnecessary damage to others' land;
  (c) Reasonable use theory: utility of use is balanced against the gravity of harm from that use.

