(1) Secured transactions involve transactions based on credit and are governed by UCC Art. 9. How it generally works:
  (i) One party (debtor) receives something from another party (creditor or secured party) without paying immediately;
  (ii) To ensure debtor will pay eventually, debtor gives creditor rights to a piece of debtor's property as collateral (i.e., a security interest);
(2) Security interest ("SI"): a right given to creditor in debtor's property;
  (i) Collateral: property in which creditor obtains rights;
  (ii) Right allows creditor to take or sell property if the debtor fails to fulfill the credit obligation (i.e., debtor doesn't pay creditor);
  (iii) Arrangement memorialized in a security agreement;
(3) Attaching & perfecting security interests:
  (i) Attachment: process by which collateral is used to secure the creditor's interest; Effect: once a SI attaches, creditor has a right to take the collateral if debtor defaults;
  (ii) Perfection: process by which creditor secures her rights in the collateral as it relates to third parties; arises where third parties also have an interest in the same piece of collateral; creditor must perfect her SI to have a greater interest in the collateral over third parties.

