cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Classifying the type of collateral involved in a transaction is important in determining how it's secured; the main categorizations are as follows:
(2) Tangible goods (four types):
  (i) Farming goods: items used/produced in farming (e.g., crops);
  (ii) Consumer goods: items used for personal, household purposes;
  (iii) Inventory: goods kept for sale or lease;
  (iv) Equipment: catchall for tangible items that do not fit above (e.g., factory machinery);
(3) Intangible goods (most common of many types):
  (i) Instruments: writings representing the right to be paid money (e.g., promissory notes, checks, etc.);
  (ii) Documents: writings representing the right to receive goods (e.g., bills of lading, receipts, etc.);
  (iii) Chattel paper: record evidencing an obligation and SI in goods or a lease of goods (for example, a promissory note and security agreement);
  (iv) Accounts: a right to payment not evidenced by an instrument or chattel (i.e., accounts receivable); for example, money owed to a dentist after seeing a patient; does not include deposit accounts, investment property, or commercial tort claims;
  (v) Deposit accounts: bank accounts;
  (vi) General intangibles: for example, patent rights, software.

