cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Consignments are transactions where an owner of goods/consignor (e.g., manufacturer or wholesaler) delivers goods to a merchant (consignee) for the purpose of sale:
(2) Consignment as SI:
  (i) Consignment can be considered a SI if inventory consignee is selling on consignment is difficult to distinguish from inventory consignee actually owns;
  (ii) Where a consignee/merchant owns inventory that could be mistaken by a creditor of consignee for similar inventory that is on consignment (i.e., owned by consignor), the consignment is considered a SI and consignor must comply with Art. 9 to give notice to consignee's creditors;
(3) Requirements (consignor must comply with Art. 9 to protect her interest in consigned goods against consignee's creditors if):
  (i) Consigned goods are worth $1,000 or more;
  (ii) Consignor did not use goods for personal, family, or household purposes (for example, consigned used clothes not covered by Art.;
  (iii) Consignee/merchant:
  (a) Deals in goods of that kind under a name other than the name of the person making delivery;
  (b) Is not an auctioneer;
  (c) Is not generally known by creditors to be substantially engaged in selling goods of others.

