cards.backMarkdown:
(1) SIs are created by contract (security agreement), and security agreements are typically:
  (i) in writing,
  (ii) signed by the debtor,
  (iii) include a description of the collateral;
  (iv) Once a SI attaches, it is secured, meaning creditor has a right to take the collateral if debtor defaults (i.e., fails to pay);
(2) Requirements for attachment (three requirements for a SI to attach):
  (i) Valid security agreement:
  (a) agreement memorializing SI;
  (b) may be evidenced by
(1) an authenticated security agreement or
(2) creditor's possession or control of collateral;
  (c) Authenticated security agreement: record authenticated by debtor that describes collateral;
  (d) Signing, initialing, etc. is adequate proof of authentication;
  (e) Agreement must reasonably identify collateral;
  (ii) Value:
  (a) Secured party (i.e., creditor) must give value to create a SI;
  (b) For Example: creditor loans debtor money or delivers equipment in exchange for SI;
  (c) Almost any consideration is sufficient;
  (iii) Rights in collateral:
  (a) debtor must have rights in property he offers as collateral;
  (b) Ownership or possessory interest is usually sufficient.

