cards.backMarkdown:
(1) UCC Art. 9 generally gives discretion to parties to create their own terms regarding security agreements. Below are common issues:
  (i) After-acquired property clauses: extends the SI to property acquired by the debtor after signing the security agreement;
  (ii) Future advances:
  (a) Security agreements may contemplate future loans/advances from creditor to debtor based on debtor's present collateral or collateral to be acquired in the future;
  (b) In such cases, a new security agreement is not required;
  (c) For Example: L loans $2000 to D secured by inventory in D's business; security agreement provides for future advances; D may get additional loans in the future from L;
  (iii) Specification clauses:
  (a) Parties may include clauses specifying terms and/or creating provisions for potential events;
  (b) For Example: parties may define what constitutes a default, may provide for acceleration of payments upon the happening of a certain event (e.g., one missed payment), etc.

