cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: A single piece of the debtor's property may serve as collateral for multiple creditors who all have their own security interest; perfection is relevant to priority of the interests; once a SI is attached it is enforceable, but it must be perfected in order to give its holder (creditor) priority over other potential SIs to which collateral may be attached;
(2) Significance of perfection: a perfected SI has maximum priority over collateral as compared to other unperfected SIs in that collateral;
  (i) Filing;
  (ii) Taking possession;
  (iii) Automatic perfection (PMSI);
  (iv) Control.

