cards.backMarkdown:
(1) There are three primary ways a SI can be perfected:
  (i) Filing financing statement (usually filed with state office):
  (a) Requirements (financing statement must):
(1) Identify debtor: name must exactly match (if debtor is business org., name must match Art. of Incorporation); Identify secured party/creditor; Contain an adequate description of collateral; and
(4) Authorization for filing must be obtained from debtor (usually security agreement itself satisfies this requirement);
  (ii) Taking possession ("pledged collateral"):
  (a) Secured party may perfect a SI in many types of collateral simply by taking possession; for example, goods (pawnshop), negotiable documents, instruments;
  (b) Certain intangible collateral cannot be perfected by possession; for example, accounts, certificate of title goods, electronic chattel paper, general intangibles;
  (iii) Automatic perfection & PMSIs:
  (a) In some transactions, once collateral is attached, perfection occurs automatically;
  (b) PMSI = purchase money security interest;
  (iv) Motor vehicles: SIs in vehicles are perfected by notation on the vehicle's certificate of title.

