cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: PMSIs are superpriorities, meaning they are superior to prior perfected SIs in the same goods, subject to the below conditions; PMSI in inventory (has priority over other SIs in the inventory or proceeds (instruments, chattel paper, identifiable cash proceeds) if):
  (i) PMSI is perfected when debtor takes possession of inventory;
  (ii) Other parties who filed their SIs in inventory receive authenticated notification of the PMSI before debtor takes possession of inventory;
  (iii) Notification must state that PMSI will be taken in debtor's inventory and describe kind and type of inventory;
(3) PMSI in goods (non-inventory or livestock):
  (i) Has priority over other SIs in the same goods and their proceeds if PMSI is perfected before or within 20 days after debtor receives possession of the collateral;
  (ii) No requirement that secured party notify other SI holders;
(4) Conflicting PMSIs (where there are multiple PMSIs in the same collateral, priority goes to):
  (i) Secured party who has PMSI as the seller of the collateral (as opposed to lender),
  (ii) Otherwise, first secured party to file or perfect;
  (iii) For Example: A takes $300 loan from bank to buy $500 TV, giving bank SI in TV, then A signs $200 credit agreement with TV store to complete purchase; store, as seller of collateral, has priority over bank as lender.

