cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Judicial lien creditors ("JLCs") are those who acquire a lien on collateral through judicial attachment, levy, etc.; Perfected secured party vs. JLC:
  (i) Prior perfected SI prevails;
  (ii) JLC prevails only if they become JLCs before a secured party files or perfects;
  (iii) Future advances: if secured party makes future advances to debtor, secured party has priority over future advances if:
  (a) Future advance was made before, or within 45 days, after lien arose, or
  (b) Future advance was made without knowledge of the lien;
(3) Unperfected secured party vs. JLC:
  (i) JLC prevails;
  (ii) PMSI grace period exception: secured party who attaches a PMSI in collateral before JLC acquires an interest in collateral has priority if it files within 20 days after debtor receives collateral.

