cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Upon default, a secured party may take possession of collateral without judicial process or collect on non-goods via authenticated notification; Note: default is defined in security agreement; not defined by Art. 9.; Reclaiming possession: reclaiming possession through self-help is allowed as long as no breach of the peace occurs;
  (i) Breach of the peace: repossession made over debtor's protest;
  (ii) Violence, threats of violence, breaking and entering, etc. will likely constitute a breach of the peace;
  (iii) Simple trespass in order to repossess property is permissible;
  (iv) For Example: permissible to unlock and hot wire a car used as collateral if the car is sitting in a driveway;
(3) Collection rights:
  (i) When collateral is non-goods (for example, accounts or instruments), upon default the secured party can notify the person owing the debtor (account debtor);
  (ii) Secured party must send authenticated notification to account debtor stating that amount due has been assigned and payment must be made to secured party;
  (iii) Upon notification, account debtor can only discharge his obligation by payment to secured party;
  (iv) For Example: A loans B $10,000, for which A receives a promissory note; A takes out a loan from C for $5,000 using B's promissory note as collateral; A defaults on C's loan; C may notify B of A's default and require that B pay C on the promissory note.

