cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Upon default, a secured party can dispose of collateral (i.e., sell, lease, etc.) as long as it is done in a commercially reasonable manner;
  (i) Surplus: sale generates more than remaining obligation; secured party must pay debtor any surplus;
  (ii) Deficiency: sale generates less than remaining obligation; debtor is still liable for amount remaining;
  (iii) Exception: neither party is liable for surplus or deficiency if underlying transaction involves: accounts, chattel paper, payment intangibles, or promissory notes;
(5) Right to redeem: until secured party has sold collateral or discharged debt by retaining collateral (i.e., strict foreclosure) debtor or any other secured party may redeem collateral by paying all remaining obligations plus reasonable expenses incurred for repossession.

