cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Secured parties are liable for failure to comply with Art. 9; Remedies available:
  (i) Actual damages: debtor can recover damages reasonably calculated to put her in the position she would be in had no violation occurred;
  (ii) Damages for consumer goods: if collateral involved is consumer goods, debtor is entitled to at least 10% of the cash price of the goods plus interest charges to be paid over the life of the loan;
  (iii) Loss of deficiency judgment: secured party may lose right to deficiency judgment;
  (a) Non-consumer transactions (the rebuttable presumption rule):
(1) Value of collateral seized is presumed equal to debt owed unless the secured party proves otherwise;
  (b) Consumer transactions (courts take one of three approaches):
(1) Follow rebuttable presumption rule;
(2) Deny secured party deficiency judgment;
(3) Allow secured party to recover deficiency minus actual damages debtor can prove.

