cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Act by D: requires some volitional movement
(2) Intent: specific or general;
  (i) Specific: intent to bring about a specific harm;
  (ii) General: substantial certainty that tortious conduct will result from D's act;
(3) Causation: substantial factor; D's conduct must be a substantial factor in bringing about the resulting harm;
(4) Transferred intent doctrine (arises when D acts with the intent to commit a given tort but):
  (i) commits original tort against a different person than intended;
  (ii) commits a different tort than intended against original person;
  (iii) commits different tort against different person than intended;
  (iv) D's original intent transfers to the tort actually committed and/or person actually harmed, resulting in D's liability;
  (v) Applies only to: assault, battery, false imprisonment, trespass
(5) Damages: compensatory (i.e., monetary) damages; punitive damages are available for torts committed with malice.

