cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Two separate but similar torts; the difference is the level of interference with P's property and the damages P can recover; Elements:
  (i) D intentionally interferes with P's right of possession in tangible personal property (chattel);
  (a) Interference usually occurs through dispossession (depriving P of his possessory rights in chattel) or damaging P's chattel;
  (b) Trespass: minor interference or damage;
  (c) Conversion: significant interference or damage that justifies D paying the chattel's full value;
  (d) A longer and/or more damaging use of P's chattel gives rise to conversion;
  (ii) Intent;
  (iii) Causation;
  (iv) Damages: P must have some loss of use;
  (a) Trespass: P can recover cost of repair or rental value of chattel;
  (b) Conversion: P can recover full market value at the time of conversion or repossess the chattel (replevin).

