(1) Requirements for all defenses:
  (i) Reasonable belief: D must reasonably believe a tort is being or about to be committed;
  (ii) Proper timing: tort must be in progress or imminent;
  (iii) Reasonable force: must be proportionate to threat of harm;
(2) Self-defense:
  (i) No duty to retreat (except a minority of jurisdictions impose a duty to retreat before using deadly force if retreat can be done safely);
  (ii) Only available to initial aggressor if initial threat has terminated or D responds to non-deadly force with deadly force;
(3) Defense of others:
  (i) D must have reasonable belief that the person he is aiding would have the right of self-defense;
  (ii) D may use as much force as he could have used if the injury was threatened to him (i.e., if he was acting in self-defense);
(4) Defense of property:
  (i) Available to prevent tort against property;
  (ii) Reasonable force may be used, but force that is deadly or causes serious bodily harm is not allowed for defense of property alone;
  (iii) Unavailable if initial actor had a privilege to enter land (e.g., recapturing chattel);
  (iv) Reasonable mistake only allowed as to whether an intrusion occurred, not whether privilege existed.

