cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: A defense to torts against property (trespass to land, trespass to chattel, conversion) in which D damages P's property in an effort to avoid a greater danger;
  (i) D's interference with P's property must be reasonably necessary to avoid an immediate threatened injury;
  (ii) threatened injury must be more serious than the interference undertaken to avert it;
(3) Public necessity:
  (i) Absolute defense;
  (ii) D's invasion of P's property must be reasonably necessary to protect the community or a large group of people;
  (iii) Absolute defense: P cannot recover any damages
(4) Private necessity:
  (i) Limited defense;
  (ii) D invades P's property to protect his own property or self or small group;
  (iii) Limited defense: P can only recover damages for actual harm to D's property, unless D trespassed for P's benefit;
(5) Property owner liability:
  (i) If an owner repels or expels a trespasser who interfered with or invaded owner's property out of a valid necessity (e.g., P seeks shelter from terrible storm);
  (ii) Owner will be liable for any damage caused.

