cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: 1st Amend. considerations arise when defamation involves a public figure, public official, and/or a matter of public concern;
(2) Public figures, public officials;
  (i) Public figure: one who has pervasive fame or notoriety, or who voluntarily assumes a central role in a public matter;
  (ii) Public official: public office holder;
(3) Additional elements;
  (i) Fault: P must prove D was at fault; standards differ for public vs. private figures:
  (ii) Public official or figure: actual malice standard (knowledge of the statement's falsity or reckless disregard to whether it was false);
  (iii) Private figure: negligence standard;
(4) Falsity:
  (i) Public officials and public figures must prove falsity;
  (ii) Private figures must prove falsity only if speech pertains to matter of public concern;
  (iii) If private figure/private speech, states may require D to prove truth.

