cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Damages depend on the type of plaintiff, content, and whether the defamatory statement constitutes libel, slander, or slander per se;
(2) Libel: a written defamatory statement;
  (i) Public figures and public officials who prove "actual malice" may recover "presumed damages" for reputational harm without any proof;
  (ii) Private figures who prove negligence may recover "presumed damages" only if the speech relates to a matter of private concern;
  (iii) If public concern, private figures may recover only proved actual damages;
  (iv) Note: TV and radio broadcasts are considered libel;
(2) Slander: a spoken defamatory statement;
  (i) P must prove "special damages" unless the statement constitutes slander per se;
  (ii) Special damages: a specific economic loss;
(3) Slander per se (a defamatory statement that either):
  (i) Adversely reflects on P's business or professional reputation;
  (ii) Claims that P has a loathsome disease;
  (iii) Claims that P committed a crime of moral turpitude;
  (iv) Imputes a woman's chastity.

