cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Consent, truth, and privilege may be valid defenses to defamation;
  (i) For Example: P may consent to an organization investigating her and sharing its findings with potential employers;
(3) Truth: allegedly defamatory statement is true; truth is a complete defense to a defamation claim;
  (i) Absolute privilege: protects statements by govt. officials in their official capacity;
  (ii) Qualified privilege (D's liability for defamatory statements is limited where):
  (a) D invites the statement and/or recipient has an interest; for example, employment reference, credit report, letter of recommendation;
  (b) statement is in the public interest; for example, book reviews, statement to a parole board.

