cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: An existing statute may establish a standard of care, in which case the statutory standard imposed by the statute will replace the general common law standard of reasonable care;
  (i) P must prove that harm suffered is the type the statute was meant to prevent;
  (ii) P is in class of victims statute was meant to protect;
  (iii) Statute applies a standard of conduct—says what to do or not to do;
(3) Statutory standard of care does not apply if:
  (i) Compliance is more dangerous than non-compliance;
  (ii) Compliance is impossible under the circumstances;
(4) Negligence per se:
  (i) Violation of the statute means P must only prove causation, not breach of duty;
  (ii) Under majority rule, that violation of the statute establishes a conclusive presumption of duty and breach of duty;
  (iii) Compliance does not automatically clear D of liability.

