cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Owners and occupiers of land may have a duty of care for anticipated trespassers and child trespassers; same standard of care applies for owners and occupiers; Unknown or undiscovered trespassers: no duty owed; Anticipated trespassers (where owner has reason to believe of trespassers on her land):
  (i) Activities: owner has duty of reasonable care in carrying out activities on her property;
  (ii) Dangerous conditions: owner has duty to make safe or warn of any known, concealed, man-made hazards;
  (iii) Note: this is rare; look for spring guns, traps, etc.;
(4) Attractive nuisance doctrine for child trespassers:
  (i) Owner must take reasonable care to eliminate dangers on her property or protect children from those dangers if:
  (a) She is aware or should be aware of a dangerous condition on her property;
  (b) She knows or should know children are in the vicinity;
  (c) The condition is likely to cause injury given a child's inability to appreciate the risk;
  (d) The magnitude of the risk outweighs its utility or the expense of remedying it.
(1) Licensee: one who enters land with owner's permission for his own purpose or business (i.e., not for landowner's benefit); For Example: relatives, friends, social guests; Invitee: one who enters land held open to the public or who enters with owner's permission to confer a commercial benefit; For Example: store patron, concert-goer; Duty of care owed:
  (i) Activities carried out on property: reasonable care;
  (ii) Known dangerous conditions: duty to warn or make safe;
  (iii) Duty to inspect:
  (a) Licensees, no duty;
  (b) Invitees, owners have duty to conduct a reasonable inspection for non-obvious dangers and make them safe;
  (c) May be non-delegable, businesses that hold property open to the public have a non-delegable duty to keep premises safe for customers;
(4) Scope of duty: limited by scope of the invitation/license; owner's duty extends only to those areas where one is an invitee or licensee (e.g., store owner does not owe duty of care in employees-only area); Note: police and firefighters are considered licensees, but cannot recover for injuries suffered in the line of duty if the injury results from a risk inherent in the job.

