cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: Establishes that it is fair under the law to hold D responsible for P's injuries; Foreseeability:
  (i) Measuring stick for proximate cause;
  (ii) D is liable for the foreseeable outcome of his conduct;
  (iii) Note: an outcome does not have to be likely to be foreseeable; unlikely things are often foreseeable on the MBE; if it's reasonably possible, it's probably foreseeable;
(3) Direct causes: if P's injury is the direct consequence of D's negligent conduct, D is liable unless the outcome is unusually bizarre or unpredictable; Indirect causes:
  (i) Intervening forces that occur after D's conduct to cause P's injuries will not cut off D's liability if they are foreseeable;
  (ii) An intervening force is usually foreseeable if either:
  (a) It is a normal response or reaction to D's negligent act, or
  (b) D's negligence increased the risk that an intervening force would cause harm to P;
  (iii) Injuries to rescuers are usually considered foreseeable;
(5) "Eggshell Plaintiff Rule": D takes P as he finds him and is liable for the full extent of P's injuries, regardless of whether they are foreseeable;

