cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: P must prove damages, which are not presumed in negligence cases; nominal damages are not available; Types of damages:
  (i) Personal injury: D must compensate P for all damages; includes past, present, and prospective damages; economic and non-economic damages are recoverable;
  (ii) Property damage: P can recover reasonable cost of repairs; if property is irreparable, damages are the full market value at the time the accident occurred;
  (iii) Punitive damages: only recoverable if D's conduct is wanton and willful, reckless, or malicious; usually not available in negligence cases; more common with intentional torts;
(3) Non-recoverable damages (P can never recover for):
  (i) Interest from the date of damage in personal injury cases;
  (ii) Attorneys' fees;
(4) Duty to mitigate: P must take reasonable steps to mitigate damages.

