cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Comparative negligence:
  (i) D can establish that P's injuries are at least partially the result of P's own negligence;
  (ii) Fact-finder apportions fault between P and D by percentage and reduces P's recoverable damages accordingly;
  (iii) Partial/modified comparative negligence: P can only recover damages if he was less than 50% at fault (or 50% or less in some states, and over 50% can make claim inactionable);
  (iv) Pure comparative negligence: P can recover damages even if he was more than 50% at fault;
(2) Contributory negligence:
  (i) P is barred from recovery if D establishes that P's negligence contributed to her injuries;
  (ii) Last clear chance defense: P can rebut D's contributory negligence claim by proving D had the last clear chance to avoid the injury-causing accident;
(3) Assumption of risk:
  (i) D can deny P's recovery by establishing that P assumed the risk of damage caused by D's act;
  (ii) Requirements (D must show):
  (a) P knew of the risk (subjective standard; but knowledge can be inferred from facts);
  (b) P voluntarily proceeded in the face of that risk
(4) Express assumption: D can assume risk by agreement (e.g., exculpatory clause); less likely to be enforced if part of adhesion K;

