cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: P may recover for emotional distress resulting from D's negligence; NIED Elements:
  (i) D's negligence results in a close risk of bodily harm to P;
  (a) P must be in "zone of danger" to recover;
  (b) For Example: D's act must have nearly caused physical harm to P;
  (ii) D's negligence results in P's severe emotional distress P exhibits some physical manifestation attributable to her emotional distress:
  (a) Symptoms can be instantaneous or appear days later;
  (b) Non-physical symptoms: states are split on this element; many allow severe emotional distress alone;
  (iii) Note: on essays, note the distinction; given the split, an MBE question is unlikely to turn on this element;
  (iii) Bystander claims (P-bystanders outside the zone of danger may recover for emotional distress resulting from D's negligence if):
  (a) P and the injured person are closely related;
  (b) P was present at the scene of the injury;
  (c) P personally observed or perceived the event;
  (iv) Special situations:
  (a) If above elements are not met, P may still recover where D's negligence creates a great likelihood of emotional distress;
  (b) For Example: Erroneous report of relative's death, mishandling of corpse.

