cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Property damage from trespassing animals:
  (i) Animal owners are strictly liable for reasonably foreseeable damage resulting from their animal's trespass on another's property;
  (ii) Does not apply to household pets;
(2) Personal injuries:
  (i) Wild animals: owners are strictly liable to licensees and invitees for unprovoked injuries caused by their wild animals;
  (ii) Domestic animals: no strict liability unless owners know of their animal's unusually dangerous propensities;
  (iii) For Example: if a dog has previously bitten people, its owner is strictly liable; but the negligence standard applies if this is the first time this dog has bitten anyone;
(3) Trespassers cannot recover: trespassers are generally not entitled to recovery under strict liability.

