cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Elements:
  (i) D is a commercial supplier:
  (a) Suppliers have a strict duty to supply safe goods;
  (b) Commercial supplier: one who routinely deals in the product sold, including any merchant in the stream of commerce;
  (c) For Example: manufacturer, distributor, supplier;
  (d) Casual sellers, service providers are not suppliers;
  (ii) Product is defective: Defect must make product unreasonably dangerous;
  (iii) Defective product was actual and proximate cause of P's injury: Product must not be substantially altered between leaving commercial supplier and reaching consumer;
  (iv) P used the product in a foreseeable manner: P's misuse of the product can be foreseeable;
  (v) Who can sue: foreseeable users or bystanders; For Example: buyers as well as their guests, employees, family, etc.;
  (vi) Damages: P can recover for physical injury or property damage, but not solely for economic losses.

