cards.backMarkdown:
(1) General Rule: Implied in every sale of goods is a warranty of merchantability and warranty of fitness for a particular purpose (if applicable); Implied warranties:
  (i) Merchantability: seller warrants that goods are of average acceptable quality (i.e., without defects) and generally fit for their ordinary purpose;
  (ii) Fitness for particular purpose:
  (a) if seller
  (b) knows or has reason to know the particular purpose for which buyer is purchasing,
  (c) buyer relies on seller's skills or judgment, then
  (d) seller implies that goods are fit for that purpose;
  (e) For Example: a shoe store salesperson helping a buyer find ideal running shoes for running on trails;
  (iii) Who can sue: Implied warranty protection extends to a buyer's family, household, and guests who suffer personal injury;
  (iv) Elements:
  (a) Warranty: existence of an implied warranty;
  (b) Breach: product fails to live up to applicable warranty;
  (c) Causation: actual and proximate;
  (d) Damages: personal, property, and economic are all recoverable;
  (e) Defenses: assumption of risk, contributory and comparative negligence.

