cards.backMarkdown:
(1) In General: D may be liable if a product falls short of an affirmative representation made to buyer;
  (i) a statement of material fact or promise regarding goods sold that becomes part of the basis of the bargain;
  (ii) Any consumer or bystander can sue for breach;
  (iii) Bystanders need not have relied on the express warranty, as long as the original purchaser did;
(3) Elements (same as for implied warranties):
  (i) Express warranty: relied upon by purchaser;
  (ii) Breach: product fails to live up to the warranty;
  (iii) Causation: actual and proximate;
  (iv) Damages: personal, property, and economic loss
(4) Defenses: assumption of risk, contributory and comparative negligence;
  (i) Seller will be liable for any misrepresentation made in the course of a sale if:
  (a) Seller made a misrepresentation regarding a material fact concerning the quality or use of the goods;
  (b) Seller intended to induce reliance by buyer;
  (c) The misrepresentation induced justifiable reliance;

