cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Intestate succession issues arise where:
  (i) Decedent dies without a will;
  (ii) Decedent's will does not dispose of all of her property; E.g., a gift in the will fails or the will lacks a residuary clause;
  (iii) Decedent's will is denied probate; E.g., will is successfully contested or improperly executed.
(2) Varying statutory schemes: states have varying rules for how decedent's assets are distributed through intestate succession (i.e., who is entitled to distributed assets and the amounts distributed); Note: given this variation, questions involving distribution of assets via intestate succession often provide information on how a hypothetical statute would provide for asset distribution;
(3) Terminology:
  (i) "Heir" vs. "beneficiary": heir is one who takes by intestate succession; beneficiary is one named in a will or trust;
  (ii) "Issue" and "descendants": often used interchangeably to describe heirs or descendants of decedent;
  (iii) "Gifts," "devises," and "bequests": used interchangeably to refer to property disposed of via a will;
  (iv) "Estate": roughly refers to property decedent owned upon death.

