cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Disclaimers: one may disclaim an interest that otherwise would pass to them from a decedent or decedent's estate;
  (i) Requirements:
  (a) for fed. tax purposes, disclaimer must be in writing, irrevocable, and filed within nine months of decedent's death;
  (b) states may impose additional requirements, although most are satisfied by compliance with fed. requirements;
  (ii) Effect: interest passes as if the disclaiming party predeceased decedent;
(2) Advancements: gifts made during testator or decedent's life with the intent that the gift be applied against any share the heir or beneficiary inherits from decedent/testator's estate;
  (i) Common law: gifts were automatically deducted from beneficiary/heir's remaining interest;
  (ii) Modern requirement: in most states, gifts to beneficiary/heir during testator/decedent's life are advancements only if either
  (a) decedent declared her intent to make the gift an advancement in a contemporaneous writing,
  (b) beneficiary/heir acknowledged the gift to be an advancement in writing;
(3) Applicability beyond intestacy: the above rules generally apply to gifts/interests that pass in forms beyond intestacy, e.g., by will.

