cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Requirements: will is valid if it complies with the state's specific formalities; generally, in most states a will must be at least:
  (i) In writing;
  (ii) Signed by testator: any mark intended to be a signature suffices; if testator is incapable of signing, must be signed by another in her presence and by her direction;
  (iii) Signed by at least two witnesses: must see testator sign the will and must sign as witnesses in testator's presence in a reasonable time;
  (i) Licensed notary satisfies this requirement in many states;
  (ii) "Testator's presence" = line or range of senses, although many states require witnesses be in testator's line of sight;
  (iii) Modern approach is "conscious presence," where the testator must be aware, but does not actually need to see the signature;
  (iv) UPC allows signature a reasonable time after the testator's signature.
(2) Attestation clause: clause included immediately between testator and witness signatures in a will, which sets forth the above required elements and that they were satisfied. Constitutes prima facie evidence of the facts recited in the clause (i.e., that execution requirements have been satisfied).

