cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Competency: witnesses must be of sufficient maturity and mental capacity to understand and appreciate the nature of what they witness and attest to. I.e., witness could sufficiently testify in court if required;
(2) Interested witnesses (where a witness stands to benefit under the will):
  (i) At common law, entire will could not be probated (mostly abolished);
  (ii) Majority rule: will is valid but gift to witness-beneficiary is void;
  (iii) Exceptions (interested witness can still be a beneficiary where either):
  (a) there were two other witnesses who were disinterested (i.e., three total witnesses, two of whom were disinterested),
  (b) interested witness would take if there was no will (i.e., interested witness would have taken as a descendant through intestate succession, then they could take the lesser of an intestate share or bequest);
(3) UPC: presence of interested witness does not invalidate a will or any part of it.

