cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Capacity (for a will to be valid, the person executing the will must be 18 or older and have mental capacity):
  (i) Age is determined at the time the will is executed;
  (ii) Mental capacity means testator, at the time of will execution, must understand:
  (a) Act: the nature of his act (i.e., that he is executing a will);
  (b) Property: the nature and extent of his property;
  (c) People: persons who are the natural objects of his bounty;
  (d) Nature of Disposition: how the above three factors relate and formulate a scheme of distribution;
  (iii) Rebuttable presumption exists that testator had mental capacity. Physical ailments, drug addiction do not raise a presumption of incapacity.
(2) Testamentary intent (testator must intend that the instrument operates as his will):
  (i) Usually established by provisions in the will (e.g., "I, Testator X, hereby declare that this is my last will");
  (ii) Present intent required: testator must have present testamentary intent (i.e., intent to make a will in the future is insufficient);
  (iii) Extrinsic evidence is allowed to prove requisite intent or lack thereof.

