cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Revocation by written instrument (a will or any part of it can be revoked or changed as long as there is):
  (i) Intent: present intent to revoke;
  (ii) Formalities: instrument revoking the will is made with the same formalities required for will execution.
(2) Revocation by physical act (a will may be revoked in most states by burning, tearing, or otherwise destroying the will):
  (i) Present intent required: testator must intend to revoke at the time of the physical act;
  (ii) Act by another (revocation by proxy): a person other than testator may revoke the will by physical act if done at testator's direction and in testator's presence;
(3) Partial revocation:
  (i) revocation may be accomplished by making marks of cancellation on the will (e.g., crossing out provisions) in most states;
  (ii) where such marks are found on a will known to have last been in testator's possession, a presumption is created that the marks were made by testator with the requisite intent to revoke.

