cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Revival: where a will is revoked and the revoking instrument is subsequently revoked, the original will is presumptively revived;
  (i) Exception: revoked will is not revived if testator's statements or other evidence make clear she did not intend to revive the prior will;
  (ii) Re-execution: a revoked will may be re-executed by a subsequent will or codicil if testamentary formalities are satisfied;
(2) Dependent Relative Revocation (DRR): court doctrine under which a court disregards a revocation that was done to create an alternative disposition to the original will, but was based on a mistake of fact or law;
  (i) Court will apply DRR and revive the revoked will if doing so would come closer to giving effect to what testator tried, but failed, to do than would intestate succession;
  (ii) Requirements (court may apply DRR (ignore will revocation) where):
  (a) Revocation was premised on some mistake of law or fact;
  (b) Revocation would not have occurred absent testator's mistaken belief that some other plan for disposition of property was valid;
  (c) The originally revoked will is closer to testator's preference than would be intestate succession.

