cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Anti-lapse statutes (a gift that would otherwise lapse vests in the predeceased beneficiary's descendants, who become substitutes):
  (i) Application: lapsed gift will be saved if predeceased beneficiary was
  (a) a relative of testator (usually descendants only);
  (b) had descendants;
  (ii) Who may be substituted: some states allow only testator's descendants, while others (and UPC) allow any of testator's relatives;
(2) Lapse in the residue (can arise where a bequest is made to a person who predeceases testator and the anti-lapse statute does not apply (e.g., predeceased beneficiary was not testator's relative)):
  (i) Common law: lapsed gift passes to testator's heirs via intestacy;
  (ii) Modern view: residuary beneficiaries who survive testator and deceased beneficiary take the deceased beneficiary's share;
(3) Class gifts:
  (i) if a will makes a gift to a class of people and a class member predeceases testator, surviving class members take predeceased's gift absent an alternative provision in testator's will;
  (ii) Exception: if an anti-lapse statute applies to the predeceasing class member (e.g., predeceased was testator's relative and has surviving descendants), gift vests in predeceased's descendants, not the class.

