cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Valid Ks to make, not make, or revoke a will are generally enforceable:
  (i) Governed by K law and Ks regarding wills are not considered wills;
  (ii) K requirements must be satisfied (e.g., mutual assent, consideration).
(2) Writing required (most states require Ks involving wills to be in writing):
  (i) Additional requirements: UPC and some states also require either:
  (a) Provisions in the will state the material provisions of the K;
  (b) Express reference in the will to the K and extrinsic evidence proving the K terms;
  (c) Writing signed by decedent/testator evidencing the K.
(3) Remedy for breach:
  (i) Constructive trust;
  (ii) Upon breach of a K to make a will (e.g., testator fails to provide for party to the K in their will), court usually probates the will and imposes a constructive trust in favor of the intended beneficiary under the K;
(4) Joint will (will of two or more people executed in a single document):
  (i) Admissible to probate upon death of either testator;
  (ii) If one testator revokes the joint will, it remains valid as the other's will;
  (iii) May be interpreted as a K for a will, particularly if executed pursuant to a promise between each party not to revoke;
(4) Mutual will:
  (i) Separate wills of two or more people containing reciprocal or substantially similar provisions;
  (ii) Usually not interpreted as a K to make a will.

