  (c) Writing signed by decedent/testator evidencing the K.
(3) Remedy for breach:
  (i) Constructive trust;
  (ii) Upon breach of a K to make a will (e.g., testator fails to provide for party to the K in their will), court usually probates the will and imposes a constructive trust in favor of the intended beneficiary under the K;
(4) Joint will (will of two or more people executed in a single document):
  (i) Admissible to probate upon death of either testator;
  (ii) If one testator revokes the joint will, it remains valid as the other's will;
  (iii) May be interpreted as a K for a will, particularly if executed pursuant to a promise between each party not to revoke;
(4) Mutual will:
  (i) Separate wills of two or more people containing reciprocal or substantially similar provisions;
  (ii) Usually not interpreted as a K to make a will.

cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Common grounds for contesting a will:
  (i) Lack of capacity or testamentary intent;
  (ii) Defective execution (i.e., failure to comply with required formalities);
  (iii) Undue influence, fraud, or mistake;
  (iv) Will has been revoked;
(2) Standing to contest a will:
  (i) generally only those with a pecuniary interest have standing to contest;
  (ii) Includes beneficiaries, someone who should be a beneficiary, or someone who would benefit if decedent has died intestate;
(3) No-contest clauses:
  (i) clause in a will providing that a beneficiary loses their interest under the will if they contest it;
  (ii) does not apply to suits challenging executor appointment, jurisdiction, or asking the court to interpret the will;
(4) Application of No-Contest Clauses:
  (i) states vary on how strictly they apply no-contest clauses;
  (ii) Majority: no forfeiture of interest if beneficiary challenges in good faith and on the basis of probable cause;
  (iii) Minority: no-contest clauses given full effect regardless of challenging beneficiary's cause or intent.

