cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Undue influence (a will is invalid if executed while testator was subject to undue influence that effectively overrode testator's free will):
  (i) Requirements (will contestant has burden of proof and must show):
  (a) Influence was exerted on testator;
  (b) Testator's mind and free will were overpowered;
  (c) Testator's will would not have been executed absent undue influence;
  (ii) Presumption (a presumption of undue influence arises if):
  (a) A confidential relationship (e.g., attorney-client) existed between testator and beneficiary, who exerted influence;
  (b) Beneficiary participated to a significant degree in executing, drafting, or procuring testator's will;
  (c) Once established, burden shifts to proponent of the will (usually beneficiary) to prove the will was not induced by undue influence
(4) Fraud (where a will or one or more of its provisions are the result of fraud, the will or the provision is invalid):
  (i) Requirements (must be shown that testator has been intentionally deceived as to):
  (a) Character or content of the will or its provisions;
  (b) Facts extrinsic to the will that would induce the will or a particular provision or disposition in the will;
  (c) Testator acted in reliance on the misrepresentation (i.e., he would not have made the gift or executed the will if he knew the facts).

