cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Mistake as to nature of instrument:
  (i) Extrinsic evidence may be permitted to show that testator was mistaken as to the nature of the instrument he signed (e.g., he did not know he was signing his will);
  (ii) Mistake may nullify the testamentary intent requirement;
(2) Mistake in inducement:
  (i) No relief is available if a mistake relates to the reason testator made a will or made (or did not make) a gift in the will;
  (ii) Note: relief may be available if there is a separate ground for contesting the will (e.g., fraud, undue influence);
(3) Mistaken omission:
  (i) No relief is available and no extrinsic evidence is admissible to show that a will mistakenly omitted a provision or contains provisions that do not reflect testator's intent;
  (ii) Note: relief may be available if there is a separate ground for contesting the will (e.g., fraud, undue influence);
(4) Reformation for a mistake:
  (i) UPC allows a court to reform terms of a will to conform to testator's intent;
  (ii) Requirements: must be shown by clear and convincing evidence that a mistake of law or fact affected the will and testator's intent. Note: Now latent and patent ambiguities can be resolved with extrinsic evidence.

