cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Power of appointment is authority granted to a person (donee) enabling donee to designate a new owner of property and how they take it:
  (i) Meaning., donor-testator gives donee power of appointment;
  (ii) Usually arises with testamentary wills that create trusts;
  (iii) For Example: T's will leaves "my property to C to give to anyone that C chooses." C has a power of appointment;
(2) General vs. Special (power of appointment can be general or special):
  (i) General: donee can exercise her power in favor of anyone, including herself, her estate, her creditors, etc.;
  (ii) Special: power is exercisable in favor of a limited class of appointees; cannot include donee, her estate, creditors, or creditors of her estate;
(3) Present vs. testamentary power (appointment power may be exercisable during donee's life or only exercisable by donee's will):
  (i) Presently exercisable: one exercisable by donee during her life;
  (ii) Testamentary power: exercisable only by the donee's will;
  (iii) For Example: T leaves "all to C and on C's death to those C has appointed." C's exercise of her power of appointment is limited to her will.

