cards.backMarkdown:
(1) A trust is a fiduciary relationship in which one party (trustee) holds legal title to property for the benefit of designated beneficiaries:
  (i) Settlor: person who created the trust, giving trustee legal title to hold, manage, and administer trust property for beneficiaries;
  (ii) Revocability: trusts are generally revocable under modern statutes, unless the terms expressly state the trust is irrevocable.
(2) Express trusts (created with property owner's express intent):
  (i) Private trust: created for the benefit of certain defined and/or ascertainable persons (most common trust tested on essays); may be created inter vivos (during settlor's life) or as a testamentary trust (created by will);
  (ii) Charitable trust: created for the benefit of an indefinite class of people or the public generally;
(3) Resulting trust:
  (i) Trust implied or imposed by law, most often when an express trust fails for some reason (e.g., beneficiary is dead, trust is unenforceable or void, etc.);
  (ii) Settlor usually becomes beneficiary and trustee conveys title back to settlor; or,
  (iii) If settlor has died, settlor's estate;
(4) Constructive trust:
  (i) Not a trust, but rather an equitable remedy used in cases to rectify unjust enrichment or wrongful conduct;
  (ii) Court imposes constructive trust on property in wrongdoer's possession.

