cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Settlor with capacity to convey: same capacity as required to create a will;
(2) Settlor has a clear present intent to create a trust relationship:
  (i) Intent must be absolutely clear and settlor must understand the nature of their act (i.e., what a trust is);
  (ii) Writing not required unless as required by the Statute of Wills or Statute of Frauds (e.g., real property);
(3) Competent trustee with duties:
  (i) must name a trustee, but once established, a trust will not fail solely b/c trustee does not exist; in such cases, a trustee will be appointed;
  (ii) Trustee capacity: in most states anyone who can hold title to property can act as a trustee;
(3) Definite beneficiary (at time of trust creation, settlor must either):
  (i) Specifically identify the beneficiaries by name;
  (ii) Sufficiently describe how beneficiaries will be ascertained;
  (iii) Does not apply to charitable trusts;
  (iv) Sole trustee cannot be a sole beneficiary of a trust;
(4) Present and clear disposition of settlor's specific property in trust:
  (i) The owner has specific property they want to place in trust;
  (ii) Trust property ("res") must be specifically described or ascertainable with certainty from its description;
(5) Valid trust purpose: can be for any purpose that is not illegal, impossible, or contrary to public policy.

