cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Inter vivos (a.k.a. "living will"):
  (i) Transfer of property: property owner transfers property to another as trustee;
  (ii) Declaration of trust: property owner declares himself trustee for another;
  (iii) Delivery: if property owner declares another as trustee (i.e., settlor is not trustee), property must be delivered to trustee;
  (iv) Formalities: writing not required, but an oral trust and its terms can only be established by clear and convincing evidence;
  (v) Land as property: writing required under Statute of Frauds;
(2) Testamentary trusts (this is a trust created by will):
  (i) Trust intent, essential terms, and identification of beneficiaries must be ascertainable by either
  (a) Terms of the will itself;
  (b) Incorporation by reference (an existing writing properly incorporated by reference into the will);
  (c) Power of appointment.
(3) Pour-over provisions:
  (i) Provision in a will that devises property to a previously existing trust;
  (ii) Does not create a trust;
  (iii) Transfers property to an existing trust.

