cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Creditor issues:
  (i) because beneficiaries have limited access to trust property, their creditors are limited in accessing beneficiary's trust interest'
(2) Discretionary trust:
  (i) trustee has absolute power and discretion to make decisions regarding distribution of trust property to beneficiaries;
  (ii) Beneficiaries have no right to income until trustee exercises discretion to distribute property or income;
  (iii) Beneficiary's creditors: cannot reach the trust because beneficiary cannot compel payment from the trust; but if creditors serve trustee with process, trustee must first satisfy creditor's claims before distributing funds to beneficiary
(3) Support trust:
  (i) directs trustee to pay beneficiaries from trust as much as is necessary for beneficiary's support;
  (ii) Beneficiary's creditors: have same rights as for discretionary trust;
(4) Spendthrift trust:
  (i) prohibits beneficiaries from transferring their interests in the trust, either voluntarily or involuntarily;
  (ii) Usually included to protect beneficiary from his own carelessness;
  (iii) Beneficiary's creditors: cannot reach beneficiary's interest in the trust, but distributions to beneficiary are reachable;
(5) Exception (the following creditors can reach trust property):
  (i) spousal or child support;
  (ii) those providing basic necessities to the beneficiary;
  (iii) holders of federal or state tax liens.

