cards.backMarkdown:
(1) Distinguishing characteristics:
  (i) Indefinite beneficiaries required:
  (a) must be created in favor of a reasonably large class of indefinite beneficiaries;
  (b) cannot be for the benefit of identifiable individuals, although a trust benefitting a single charitable organization whose activities meet these requirements is acceptable;
  (c) Test: beneficiaries are indefinite and unascertainable if they are unnamed and changing over time;
  (ii) Charitable purpose:
  (a) Must be considered to benefit the public;
  (b) Effect of gift, not motive of settlor, controls (for example, a trust to build a public swimming pool on land next to settlor's house is acceptable even if settlor's motive was to use the pool);
  (c) Trust for supporting political initiatives can be charitable, including a present change in law (although cannot be a trust in favor of a political party);
  (iii) Can be perpetual:
  (a) the Rule Against Perpetuities ("RAP") does not apply to charitable trusts, as compared to private trusts, where all interests must vest within the RAP period;
(2) Modification: trust's property can be applied to different charitable purposes through the Cy Pres doctrine.

